<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	VIP Lounges
</I>
	. We began operating our first VIP Lounge at Los Cabos airport&#146;s Terminal 1 in 2011. By the end of 2015, we operated seven lounges in six Mexican airports: two in our Guadalajara airport
	(including both domestic and international lounges), and one in each of our Puerto Vallarta, Hermosillo, Tijuana, Los Cabos and Aguascalientes airports. In 2015, over 260&nbsp;thousand users were hosted in the VIP lounges in our Mexican airports, an
	increase of 43.1% from 2014. In 2016, we will open five new lounges: two in each of our Puerto Vallarta and Los Cabos airports and one in our Guanajuato airport. In Jamaica, a third party operates the sole common use lounge in the arrivals and
	departures areas, and there are five lounges operated by hotels in the arrivals area.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Convenience stores
</I>
	. In April&nbsp;2012, we began our own operation of a convenience store at the Aguascalientes airport, in which we sell magazines, soft drinks, candy and groceries, among other items, directly
	to our passengers. Subsequently, during the last quarter of 2012, we opened another two stores in Terminal 2 of the Los Cabos airport, one in the departures area and one in the check-in counters area. Due to strong performance at the Aguascalientes
	airport, we opened a second store in the departures area in October 2013 and during 2014, we added nine new stores in five airports: three in Puerto Vallarta, two in Los Cabos, two in Guanajuato, one in Hermosillo and one in La Paz. In 2015, we
	expanded our convenience store chain with the addition of five new stores in two airports: four in Guadalajara and one more in Hermosillo.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<A NAME="eolPage57"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2016, we plan to expand this business line with eight additional stores: two in each of the
	Mexicali, Morelia and Manzanillo airports and one in each of the La Paz and Los Cabos airports.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Domestic Passengers in Mexico
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Domestic passengers represented approximately 65.4% of our Mexican terminal passenger traffic in 2015. In addition, we estimate that a
	significant minority of our international passengers in Mexico are lower-income Mexicans traveling to or from the United States. Based on surveys and studies conducted during 2012 and 2013 at Guadalajara International Airport to better understand
	the consumption habits of our passengers, we believe that the spending habits of these Mexican international passengers are more similar to the spending habits of our domestic passengers, who generally purchase fewer products than other
	international passengers. However, in order to increase the consumer spending of this demographic, we have been increasing the brand recognition of commercial spaces and the products they offer, which, based on the surveys and studies we have
	conducted, we believe is likely to contribute to increased consumption among our domestic passengers and our Mexican international passengers. Partly as a result of the implementation of these strategies, consumer spending per passenger in our
	Mexican airports increased by 6.6% during 2015 as compared to 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Recovery of Costs from Checked Baggage Screening at our Mexican Airports
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2005, the Mexican government issued a policy letter (
<I>
	carta de pol&iacute;tica
</I>
	) calling for all checked baggage on all commercial
	flights to undergo a new comprehensive screening process. The new screening process required the installation of dedicated screening equipment and the manual inspection of baggage if such equipment signals the potential presence of prohibited items.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The operation of this screening equipment is the responsibility of our airline customers under the Mexican Airport Law. Because the
	Mexican Airport Law expressly provides that airlines bear the responsibility for checked baggage screening, if an airline wants us to operate the baggage screening system for them, they must enter into a contract with us that allows us to recover
	the cost of operating the equipment. However, because of uncertainty over the policy letter&#146;s implementation, the new screening process had been initially delayed. Although, as stated, the Mexican Airport Law expressly provides that airlines
	bear the responsibility for baggage screening, the fact that the policy letter is silent as to responsibility caused some of our airline customers to contend that the policy letter&#146;s intent is for airport concessionaires, such as us, to bear
	responsibility for the new screening process. In addition, certain questions have been raised regarding the constitutionality of the new screening process. Since the issuance of the policy letter, the Mexican Directorate General of Civil Aviation
	has been expected to issue implementing regulations. On November&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2012, the Mexican civil aviation authority published a recommendation (
<I>
	circular obligatoria)
</I>
	on the SCT website that, instead of modifying the legal
	responsibilities set forth in the Mexican Airport Law, attempted to facilitate contracts between parties through certain non-binding recommendations regarding issues of responsibility that had been raised by the policy letter. These non-binding
	recommendations have no legal effect unless incorporated into a valid contract.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have operated checked baggage screening equipment in
	our ten busiest Mexican airports since 2011; only flights departing from the Los Mochis airport continue to rely on manual inspection. At the end of 2015, approximately 96.9% of the passengers travelling through our Mexican airports were using the
	checked baggage system. During the first quarter of 2016, we integrated the Aguascalientes airport into the baggage screening system, which increased the percentage of baggage inspected with automated systems to 99.3%. As of
	December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, we had agreements to operate baggage screening systems with all airlines operating at our Mexican airports. Under these agreements, we negotiated certain recovery tariffs per year and these airlines agreed to hold
	harmless and indemnify us against certain types of liability that might arise in connection with the operation of the baggage screening system, in accordance with the provisions of the Mexican Airport Law.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	52
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage58"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We incur ongoing expenses to maintain and operate this equipment. Currently, the operational
	costs of the screening system has been limited to the level necessary to provide the required services to airlines, and we expect to continue recovering those costs. We also expect to incur ongoing expenses to maintain any equipment purchased, and
	we could be required to undertake significant additional capital expenditures for items such as a new screening technology or additional equipment if screening guidelines are expanded further and require that additional steps be taken to comply with
	the requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Recent Expansion and Development of Commercial Areas
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We believe that leading privatized airports typically generate a greater portion of their revenues from commercial activities than we currently
	do, which approximately ranges from 20% to 30% of total revenues. In 2015, revenues from non-aeronautical services in our airports accounted for 22.8% of our total revenues. Revenues from non-aeronautical services in our airports represent 25.4% of
	the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues of our airports. As this is a primary component of our business strategy, we have focused on increasing our revenues from commercial activities in our airports by:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
</I>
<I>
	Redesigning and expanding the space available in our airport terminals allocated to commercial activities
</I>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In order to increase our revenues from commercial activities, we have focused on expanding and redesigning the layout of certain terminals in
	our Mexican airports to allow for the inclusion of more commercial businesses, as well as to redirect the flow of passengers through our airports, increasing their exposure to the commercial areas of our airports. In October&nbsp;2013, we added 576
	square meters of commercial areas to Terminal 2 at our Los Cabos airport. This new commercial space began operations on December&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2013. In the last quarter of 2013, we built a passenger walkway through the duty-free store at this
	airport, leading passengers through the store on their way to the boarding gates. In December 2013, we added 152 square meters of commercial areas to Terminal 1 at our Guadalajara airport. In January&nbsp;2014, this commercial space in the arrivals
	zone began operations with a currency exchange service, and in the last quarter of 2014 we added a relocated and remodeled duty-free store. At the end of 2014, we added another 280 square meters of commercial areas to Terminal 1 at our Guadalajara
	airport&#146;s international boarding gates, where we also built a new food court, more retail stores and increased the square meters of two of the biggest restaurants in this airport in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In Jamaica, MBJA remodeled the commercial areas at the Montego Bay airport in 2014, adding 1,000 square meters of commercial areas, with the
	main goal of redesigning and expanding the four duty-free stores representing the most important commercial activity at the airport. Because the duty-free stores are located at the entrance to the airport&#146;s commercial area, our strategy with
	regards to the duty-free stores in Jamaica is to optimize passengers&#146; ability to quickly and easily find desired products and complete their purchase with a high level of service that encourages passengers to shop more following their traverse
	through the duty-free shops.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
</I>
<I>
	Renegotiating agreements with terminal tenants to be more consistent with market practices
</I>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have also continued improving our lease arrangements with existing tenants through the usage of royalty-based lease contracts, whereby lease
	amounts are based on tenants&#146; revenues, subject to minimum fixed amounts related to the square footage. We estimate that
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	53
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage59"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	approximately 97% of current commercial revenues could be arranged as royalty-based contracts based on the nature of our tenants&#146; operations. Approximately 98.5% of the contracts that could
	be arranged as royalty-based have already been executed under those conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
</I>
<I>
	Recovering the rights to several retail and car parking businesses previously operated at our airports by third parties
</I>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to 1999, our predecessor entered into several contracts with third-party operators to develop new spaces and modernize existing spaces at
	our twelve Mexican airports. Under these leases, the third-party operators managed the airports&#146; commercial areas and received all revenues from the operations in those areas.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We acquired our Mexican concessions from our predecessor subject to these long-term lease obligations and sought to recover rights leased to
	the third-party operators. In prior years, by compensating leaseholders for early termination of their leases, we recovered several significant retail leases and all car parking leases in our Mexican airports.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the last quarter of 2013, the lease agreements of seven convenience stores at the Hermosillo, Puerto Vallarta, Los Cabos and Guanajuato
	airports expired. Upon the expiration of the leases, we successfully took possession of the spaces from these tenants, after which we have either managed the businesses directly or repurposed the spaces in the context of further terminal expansion.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; MARGIN-LEFT:8%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Following this process, in 2014 the only remaining material commercial activity at our airports subject to a third-party lease under which
	we received only nominal revenue was the hotel at Guadalajara International Airport. A third party, Coco Club Hoteles y Morandas de M&eacute;xico, S.A. de C.V. (&#147;Coco Club&#148;), had been granted the right to operate the hotel at our
	Guadalajara airport, subject to its satisfaction of certain specific conditions at below-market rents. Because we did not believe that Coco Club satisfied all such conditions, we did not renew the lease and initiated legal proceedings against Coco
	Club to regain possession of the hotel. After Coco Club&#146;s appeal from a decision ordering the return of the hotel to us, on October&nbsp;29,&nbsp;2014, we received a final court order for eviction and took possession of the hotel. On
	October&nbsp;29, 2015, we began the demolition of the building. We have contracted with consultants to review possible projects, and plan to build a hotel, offices and commercial areas on this site.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	Recognition of Revenues from Improvements to Concession Assets
</I>
</B>
<B>
</B>
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IFRIC&nbsp;12 requires, subject to certain conditions, that the infrastructure of a service concession contract falling within its scope not be
	recognized as property, plant and equipment. It also requires that revenues obtained when the operator performs both construction or upgrade services and operating services under a single contract be recognized according to each type of service
	provided, based on the
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	54
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	fair value of consideration received at the time the service is rendered. We recognize revenues and the associated costs of improvements to concession assets that we are obligated to perform as
	established by the Master Development Programs at our Mexican airports and the Capital Development Program at the Montego Bay airport. Revenues represent the value of the exchange between ourselves and the respective governments with respect to the
	improvements, given that we construct or provide improvements to the airports as obligated under the Master Development Programs and the Capital Development Program, and in exchange, the governments grant us the right to obtain benefits for services
	provided using those assets, which are recognized as intangible assets. We have determined that our obligations per the Master Development Programs and the Capital Development Program should be considered to be a revenue-earning activity as all
	expenditures incurred to fulfill the Master Development Programs and the Capital Development Program are included in the maximum tariffs and regulated charges that we charge our customers. Therefore we recognize the revenue and expense in profit or
	loss when the expenditures are performed. The cost for such additions and improvements to concession assets is based on actual costs incurred by us in the execution of the additions or improvements, considering the investment requirements in the
	Master Development Programs and the Capital Development Program. Through bidding processes, we contract third parties to carry out such construction. The amount of revenues for these services is equal to the amount of costs incurred, as we do not
	obtain any profit margin for these construction services. The amounts paid are set at market value. As a result, revenues from improvements to concession assets do not have a cash impact on our results. Furthermore, they are not directly related to
	our passenger traffic, which is the main driver of our revenues.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Marketing Activities
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We focus our marketing activities, with respect to aeronautical services, on participation in business conferences organized by public
	organizations, such as the International Air Transport Association, and private organizations, such as the annual &#147;Routes Americas&#148; and &#147;World Routes&#148; conferences organized by United Business Media. These conferences provide a
	forum for the exchange of information relating to airlines&#146; decisions about changes in routes and flights. To lease properties and obtain related non-aeronautical services revenues, we principally rely on advertising through traditional local
	distribution channels, including newspapers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Our Mexican Airports
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, our Mexican airports served a total of approximately 27.6&nbsp;million terminal passengers. In 2015, our two principal airports that
	serve important metropolitan areas, Guadalajara International Airport and Tijuana International Airport, together represented approximately 53.1% of our Mexican airports&#146; total terminal passenger traffic. Puerto Vallarta International Airport
	and Los Cabos International Airport, our main Mexican airports serving popular tourist destinations, together accounted for approximately 26.2% of our Mexican airports&#146; total terminal passenger traffic in 2015. Guanajuato International Airport,
	which is our largest airport serving a mid-sized city, accounted for approximately 5.4% of our Mexican airports&#146; total terminal passenger traffic in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	All of our Mexican airports are designated as international airports under applicable Mexican law, meaning that they are equipped to receive
	international flights and maintain customs and immigration facilities operated by the Mexican government.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following table shows the
	sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues for each of the Mexican airports for the years indicated:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	58

<A NAME="eolPage64"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Guadalajara International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Guadalajara International Airport is our most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, air traffic movements and contribution
	to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, Guadalajara International Airport was the third busiest airport in Mexico in terms of
	commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to the SCT. In 2015, it served 9.8&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 35.4% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 66.8% of
	the terminal passengers served were domestic passengers and 33.2% were international passengers. Of the airport&#146;s international passengers, we estimate that a significant portion is Mexicans living in the United States visiting Guadalajara.
	This airport also serves many business travelers traveling to and from Guadalajara. Because the airport&#146;s passengers are predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by
	Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	Guadalajara International Airport is located approximately 20&nbsp;kilometers from the city of
	Guadalajara, which has a population (including its suburbs) of approximately 5&nbsp;million inhabitants. Guadalajara is Mexico&#146;s second largest city in terms of population and is the capital of the state of Jalisco, the country&#146;s second
	largest state in terms of population. As a major hub for the Mexican national highway system, the city of Guadalajara is an important center for both ground and air transportation. Other major cities in the state of Jalisco include Puerto Vallarta
	and Lagos de Moreno. Jalisco is an important agricultural producer, making Guadalajara an important center for agricultural commerce. The state is an important contributor to Mexico&#146;s
<I>
	maquiladora
</I>
	industry, most notably in the electronic,
	computer equipment and clothing industries. The
<I>
	maquiladora
</I>
	industry in Jalisco grew significantly in the 1990&#146;s as
<I>
	maquiladoras
</I>
	moved away from the U.S.-Mexico border seeking lower labor costs and a more diverse labor pool.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of thirteen airlines operate at the airport, the principal ones being Volaris, Aerom&eacute;xico Group and Interjet. The main
	non-Mexican airlines operating at the airport are United, American, Alaska and Delta. Airlines operating at the airport reach 52&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City, Tijuana and Los Angeles are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Guadalajara International Airport operates 24 hours daily. The airport has two operating runways, one with a length of 4,000&nbsp;meters and a
	full parallel taxiway and the other with a length of 1,800&nbsp;meters, with a threshold displacement of 300&nbsp;meters at the runway, which permits a landing distance of 1,500&nbsp;meters. The runway capacity at this airport is 39 air traffic
	movements per hour. The airport also has an Instrument Landing System (&#147;ILS&#148;) that assists pilots in poor weather. The airport&#146;s facilities include a main commercial terminal with a large parking facility and a general aviation
	building. The airport&#146;s main commercial terminal has a total area of approximately 64,500&nbsp;square meters, as well as parking facilities consisting of an additional 46,000&nbsp;square meters. The general aviation building has an additional
	1,825&nbsp;square meters. The commercial terminal has 29&nbsp;gates and 40 remote boarding positions. Of the 29&nbsp;gates, ten serve international flights and 19 serve domestic flights. Of the international gates, four have air bridges, and of the
	domestic gates, six have air bridges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, approximately 136.4&nbsp;thousand metric tons of cargo was transported through the
	airport.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	As part of our business strategy, during 2013 we continued changing the profile and category of service of almost all of
	the stores at the airport to increase brand recognition. We completed this process during the second quarter of 2014. In October&nbsp;2014, we gained possession of the onsite hotel from the previous operator, a third-party lessee from whom we had
	received no revenues. We are currently planning new business projects for this site. For more information, see &#147;Item&nbsp;4,
<I>
	Information on the Company &#150; Business Overview &#150; Our Sources of Revenues &#150; Non-Aeronautical Services
	&#150; Recent Expansion and Development of Commercial Areas &#150; Recovering the rights to several retail and car parking businesses previously operated at our airports by third parties
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We directly operate two VIP lounges in the Guadalajara airport: we operate one lounge in the international departures area and, during the
	third quarter of 2014, we opened a second lounge in the domestic departures area. In 2015, we also expanded our convenience store chain with the addition of four new stores in this airport.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	59
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage65"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We have continued to take significant steps to modernize and expand Guadalajara International
	Airport in order to improve its operations and image. These steps have included the improvement of the airport&#146;s runways and platforms, an increase in the number of remote boarding positions, the installation of an improved computer system for
	resources allocation, and expansion of the main commercial terminal, including the installation and/or modernization of air bridges, the baggage claim area, ticket counters, restrooms, hallways and gate areas. In 2014, we completed an addition of
	20&nbsp;new remote parking positions for aircraft. In addition, the international arrivals area is also being expanded, and two new aircraft parking gates will be added to this area. This expansion includes the enlargement of the customs and
	immigration facilities, as well as the departures lounge and commercial areas.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Tijuana International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Tijuana International Airport is our second most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic and air traffic movements, and fourth
	in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Tijuana International Airport was the fifth busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation traffic, according to the SCT. In 2015, it served a
	total of 4.9&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 17.6% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. Approximately 99% of the terminal passengers served were domestic passengers. Since Tijuana is located near
	the Mexico-U.S. border and is therefore a popular entry point to the United States, a majority of the airport&#146;s passengers consists of Mexican migrant workers traveling to Tijuana in order to seek work in the United States. Accordingly, the
	airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected by Mexican and U.S. economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Tijuana International
	Airport serves the city of Tijuana and surrounding areas in the State of Baja California, including the municipalities of Ensenada, Tecate and Rosarito. With a population of approximately 1.7&nbsp;million, Tijuana is the largest city in the state.
	Currently, the state of Baja California is the second largest
<I>
	maquiladora
</I>
	center in Mexico, according to INEGI data on workforce by industry. A highway connecting the city of Tijuana to the airport also extends directly to the U.S.-Mexico
	border crossing, providing convenient access to San Diego, California (which is located approximately 30&nbsp;kilometers from Tijuana International Airport) and other areas of southern California, particularly Los Angeles.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of six airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are Volaris and Aerom&eacute;xico Group. Airlines operating at this airport
	provide service to 31&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City, Guadalajara, and Guanajuato are the most popular. In addition, Aerom&eacute;xico Group flies three times weekly from Tijuana to Shanghai.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Tijuana International Airport currently operates seventeen hours daily between the hours of 7:00&nbsp;a.m. and 12:00&nbsp;a.m. However, it is
	equipped to operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for other aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway with a length of 2,960&nbsp;meters and a full
	parallel taxiway. The runway capacity at this airport is 36&nbsp;air traffic movements per hour. The airport also has an ILS that assists pilots in poor weather. It has nineteen gates serving both domestic and international travelers and six remote
	boarding positions. Of the nineteen gates, ten have air bridges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	Construction of an international bridge between our Tijuana
	airport and the United States border began in 2014 and was completed during 2015; this bridge allows passengers to cross directly to the United States using a pathway between the airport and the international border. The facility became operational
	in December&nbsp;2015. We estimate that, in the long term, approximately 45% of all passengers travelling through Tijuana International Airport will use the international bridge. For a description of the Tijuana cross-border facility, see
	&#147;Item&nbsp;5,
<I>
	Operating and Financial Review and Prospects &#150; Overview &#150; Recent Developments &#150; Tijuana Cross-Border Facility
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	60
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage66"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, approximately 18.3&nbsp;thousand metric tons of cargo was transported through the
	airport.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	A portion of the land comprising Tijuana International Airport was expropriated by the Mexican federal government in 1970
	pursuant to its power of eminent domain and is subject to certain legal proceedings by its former landholders. For a description of these legal proceedings and their potential impact on our operations, see &#147;Item&nbsp;8,
<I>
	Financial Information
	&#150; Legal Proceedings &#150; Ejido participants at Tijuana, Guadalajara and Puerto Vallarta airports
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Los Cabos International
	Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Los Cabos International Airport is our third most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, fifth in terms
	of air traffic movements and second in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Los Cabos International Airport was the sixth busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger
	traffic, according to the SCT. In 2015, it served 3.7&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 13.2% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. Approximately 72.1% of the terminal passengers served were
	international passengers. In 2014, Hurricane Odile caused the airport to suspend commercial operations for eighteen days, also causing a reduction in the total number of passengers flying to the area after the resumption of commercial flights.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The airport serves primarily tourists visiting San Jose del Cabo, Cabo San Lucas and other coastal destinations along the Trans-Peninsular
	highway of the state of Baja California Sur. Los Cabos International Airport is located approximately thirteen kilometers from the city of San Jose del Cabo, in the state of Baja California Sur. In 2015, the number of visitors to Los Cabos (San Jose
	del Cabo and the nearby city of Cabo San Lucas) was approximately 1.8&nbsp;million, according to the Mexican Immigration Institute. Visitors to this area are generally affluent and include golfers who enjoy world-class courses, as well as sport
	fishing and diving enthusiasts who are drawn by the rich marine life in the region&#146;s coastal waters.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of twenty airlines
	operate at the airport with American, Alaska, United, Interjet and Volaris being the principal ones. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to 39 destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City, Guadalajara, Los Angeles and Phoenix are
	the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Los Cabos International Airport currently operates eleven hours daily between 7:00&nbsp;a.m. and 6:00&nbsp;p.m.
	However, it is equipped to operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway measuring 3,000&nbsp;meters, and a full
	parallel taxiway to the runway. The runway capacity at this airport is 42&nbsp;air traffic movements per hour. The existing runway allows us to serve planes flying to any destination in the United States and Canada. The airport has two commercial
	aviation terminals. Terminal 1 occupies approximately 14,600&nbsp;square meters and Terminal 2 occupies approximately 38,000&nbsp;square meters. In addition, the airport has a general aviation and an FBO terminal. The airport has sixteen gates
	(eight in Terminal 1 and eight in Terminal 2), including four gates with air bridges, and fourteen remote boarding positions. We operate commercial space of approximately 2,000 square meters at Los Cabos International Airport; this space includes
	two VIP lounges and three convenience stores operated directly by us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, approximately 35.6% of the sum of our aeronautical and
	non-aeronautical revenues generated at Los Cabos International Airport was derived from non-aeronautical revenues (of which 92.9% came from commercial activities); the latter percentage is higher than any other airport of the Group.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	61
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage67"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Puerto Vallarta International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Puerto Vallarta International Airport is our fourth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic and air traffic movements and
	third in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Puerto Vallarta International Airport was the seventh busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to the
	SCT. In 2015, it served 3.6&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 13.0% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 68.7% of these terminal passengers were international passengers
	and 31.3% were domestic passengers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Puerto Vallarta International Airport is located on the Pacific coast in the state of Jalisco. The
	airport primarily serves foreign tourists and is also a popular tourist destination within Mexico. Puerto Vallarta&#146;s tourist attractions include the natural beauty of the Bay of Banderas, the area&#146;s many beaches and abundant marine
	wildlife. Puerto Vallarta is a mature tourist destination, and the completion of new resort areas including hotels and golf courses in the areas known as Nuevo Vallarta and Punta Mita is expected to bring more tourists to the area in subsequent
	years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of twenty-four&nbsp;airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are American, United, Alaska, Aerom&eacute;xico
	Group, United, Interjet and WestJet. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to 44&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations, the most popular are Mexico City, Los Angeles and Dallas. In addition, Thomson flies once weekly from Puerto
	Vallarta to London Gatwick and Manchester.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Puerto Vallarta International Airport operates 24&nbsp;hours daily. The airport has one runway
	with a length of 3,100&nbsp;meters as well as a parallel taxiway. The runway capacity at this airport is 37&nbsp;air traffic movements per hour. This airport has one main commercial terminal, an FBO terminal and a general aviation building. The
	airport has nineteen gates, of which five serve domestic flights and fourteen serve international flights, seven remote boarding positions and eleven air bridges. During 2014, we began operating two new convenience stores in the airport. During
	2015, we remodeled 6,000&nbsp;square meters in the arrivals area to improve passenger flows in the terminal, with 200&nbsp;square meters dedicated to commercial use, including one VIP lounge operated directly by us. We plan to open two more lounges
	in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, approximately 27.1% of the sum of our aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues generated at our Puerto Vallarta
	airport was derived from non-aeronautical revenues (of which 90.1% came from commercial activities).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Guanajuato International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Guanajuato International Airport is our fifth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic and sixth in air traffic movements
	and fifth in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Guanajuato International Airport was the ninth busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to the SCT.
	In 2015, it served 1.5&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 5.4% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 62.8% of the terminal passengers served were domestic passengers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Guanajuato International Airport is located in the central state of Guanajuato near the cities of Leon, Irapuato, Silao and Guanajuato,
	approximately 315&nbsp;kilometers northwest of Mexico City. The state of Guanajuato has a population of approximately 5.5&nbsp;million people according to the Mexican National Population Council and is located in Mexico&#146;s Bajio region, best
	known for its rich colonial history, agricultural sector and manufacturing industry. General Motors has an assembly plant in Silao, Guanajuato, and Mazda has a new vehicle manufacturing plant in Salamanca, Guanajuato. The local government is
	developing a &#147;dry dock&#148;, or truck loading service terminal, near the airport that we believe will increase cargo demand.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	62
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage68"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of eleven airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are Volaris,
	Aerom&eacute;xico Group and United. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to twelve&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations Tijuana, Mexico City and Houston are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Guanajuato International Airport operates 20&nbsp;hours daily between 4:00&nbsp;a.m. and 12:00&nbsp;midnight. However, it is equipped to
	operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway with a length of 3,500&nbsp;meters. The runway capacity at this
	airport is 11&nbsp;air traffic movements per hour. It has two terminals (one commercial and one general aviation), with six gates, five remote boarding positions and three air bridges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2013, we completed construction on the arrivals area, expanding it by 500 square meters. The work included new baggage claim belts and
	a re-organization of the customs and immigration facilities. As part of our business strategy, our construction during the second quarter 2013 focused on redesigning the car rental counters and increasing the advertising spaces in that area by 20%.
	During 2014, we started operating two convenience stores, one in the check-in area and one beyond the security checkpoint in the boarding area. In 2016, we plan to open another VIP lounge in the boarding area beyond the security checkpoint.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Hermosillo International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Hermosillo International Airport is our sixth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, fourth in terms of air traffic
	movements and sixth in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Hermosillo International Airport was the eleventh busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according
	to the SCT. In 2015, it served approximately 1.3&nbsp;million terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 4.9% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 94.7% of the terminal passengers served were
	domestic passengers. Many of the airport&#146;s passengers use the airport as a hub for connecting flights between other Mexican cities, particularly Mexico City, Tijuana, Guadalajara and Monterrey. Because the airport&#146;s passengers are
	predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Hermosillo International Airport serves the city of Hermosillo and four other nearby municipalities, which together have a population of
	approximately 1.0&nbsp;million, according to the Mexican National Population Council. The city of Hermosillo, which is the capital of the state of Sonora, is located approximately 260&nbsp;kilometers south of the border town of Nogales and
	130&nbsp;kilometers east of the Gulf of California. The airport is located approximately thirteen kilometers west of the city of Hermosillo. The airport is an important hub in a primarily agricultural and industrial region. Approximately
	8.3&nbsp;thousand metric tons of cargo passed through the airport in 2015. Currently, cargo transport services at this airport primarily serve the nearby Ford factory, which receives components via the airport.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of nine airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are Aerom&eacute;xico Group, Volaris, Interjet and VivaAerobus. Airlines
	operating at this airport provide service to ten&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City, Guadalajara, Monterrey and Tijuana are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Hermosillo International Airport operates eighteen hours daily between 6:00&nbsp;a.m. and 12:00&nbsp;midnight. However, it is equipped to
	operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has two runways, one with a length of 2,300&nbsp;meters and the other, a private
	aircraft runway that is not currently operating as a result of commercial considerations, with a length of 1,100&nbsp;meters. Runway
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	63
</P>

	capacity at this airport is 30&nbsp;air traffic movements per hour. The airport has nine gates and ten remote positions and includes both a commercial aviation building and a general aviation
	building for small private aircraft. An expansion of the terminal building has been planned to install two new gates with air bridges and two new apron positions by the end of 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2012, we opened a VIP lounge in the airport. As part of our business strategy, during 2013 we changed the profile and category of services
	of almost all of the stores at Hermosillo International Airport to stores with greater brand recognition and we opened a directly operated convenience store. In 2014, we added a Starbucks Coffee shop, Subway, Sunglass Hut and a second convenience
	store directly operated by us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	La Paz International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	La Paz International Airport is our seventh most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, air traffic movements and
	contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, La Paz International Airport was the twenty-first busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to the SCT. In 2015, it served
	682.4&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 2.5% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 98.6% of the terminal passengers served were domestic passengers. Because the
	airport&#146;s passengers are predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	La Paz International Airport serves the city of La Paz, located along the coast of the Gulf of California in the state of Baja California Sur,
	of which La Paz is the capital. Eco-tourism is a growing industry in La Paz due to the abundance of marine life found in the Gulf of California.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of six airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones of which are Volaris and Aerom&eacute;xico Group. Airlines operating at
	this airport provide service to twelve destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City, Guadalajara and Tijuana are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	La
	Paz International Airport operates sixteen hours daily between 7:00&nbsp;a.m. and 11:00&nbsp;p.m. However, it is equipped to operate 24 hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside
	normal business hours. The airport has one runway measuring 2,500 meters in length and a single main commercial terminal. The runway capacity at this airport is fifteen air traffic movements per hour. It also has three gates and seven remote
	boarding positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2013, we completed the construction on both the arrival and departure areas. The arrival area was enlarged by
	1,500 square meters, and two new baggage claim belts were installed. In October 2014, we opened one directly operated convenience store located in the check-in area of the airport. In 2016, we plan to open a second directly operated convenience
	store beyond the security checkpoint.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Aguascalientes International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Aguascalientes International Airport is our eighth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, air traffic movements and
	contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Aguascalientes International Airport was the twenty-third busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to the SCT. In 2015, it
	served 633.1&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 2.3% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 74.5% of the terminal passengers served were domestic passengers. Because the
	airport&#146;s passengers are predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">

</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Aguascalientes International Airport serves the city of Aguascalientes and eight surrounding
	municipalities in the central state of Aguascalientes, which is located roughly 513&nbsp;kilometers northwest of Mexico City. Manufacturing forms the basis of the region&#146;s economy. One of Nissan&#146;s main manufacturing plants in Mexico is
	located in the city of Aguascalientes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of seven airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are Aerom&eacute;xico Group,
	Volaris and Interjet. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to eight destinations. Of these destinations Mexico City, Tijuana, Dallas and Los Angeles are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Aguascalientes International Airport operates eighteen hours daily between 6:00&nbsp;a.m. and 12:00&nbsp;a.m. However, it is equipped to
	operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. It has two runways, one measuring 3,000&nbsp;meters in length and the other, a private aircraft
	runway that is not currently operating as a result of commercial considerations, measuring 1,000&nbsp;meters, and a single main commercial terminal. The runway capacity at this airport is fourteen air traffic movements per hour. The airport has
	three gates and four remote boarding locations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2013 and 2014, we continued our expansion of commercial areas operated by us, and in
	the third quarter of 2013 we opened a second convenience store in the passenger departure area. In 2015, we continued our expansion of VIP lounges with a new lounge opened at this airport and, in the first quarter of 2016, we installed a new CTX
	screening system for automated inspection of checked baggage.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Mexicali International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mexicali International Airport is our ninth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, eleventh in terms of air traffic
	movements and tenth in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Mexicali International Airport was the twenty-sixth busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic according
	to the SCT. In 2015, it served 595.6&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 2.2% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 99.3% of the terminal passengers served by this airport
	were domestic passengers. Because the airport&#146;s passengers are predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mexicali International Airport serves the city of Mexicali, in the Mexican state of Baja California, as well as the U.S. cities of Yuma,
	Arizona and Calexico, California. The city of Mexicali is located along the U.S.-Mexico border approximately 150 kilometers east of Tijuana and 80 kilometers west of Yuma, Arizona. Manufacturing forms the basis of the area&#146;s economy, most
	notably in the form of
<I>
	maquiladora
</I>
	factories, which have proliferated along the California-Baja California border.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of four
	airlines operate at the airport; the principal ones are Volaris and Aerom&eacute;xico Group. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to five destinations. Of these destinations, Mexico City and Guadalajara are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mexicali International Airport operates nineteen hours daily between 6:00&nbsp;a.m. and 1:00&nbsp;a.m. the following day. However, it is
	equipped to operate 24 hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway measuring 2,600 meters in length as well as a main commercial
	terminal and a smaller general aviation terminal. The runway capacity at this airport is fourteen air traffic movements per hour. The main commercial terminal has two gates and four remote boarding positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2016, we expect to open two new convenience stores directly operated by us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Morelia International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Morelia International Airport is our tenth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, ninth in terms of air traffic
	movements and ninth in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Morelia International Airport was the thirty-second busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic,
	according to the SCT. In 2015, it served 478.5&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 1.7% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 47.9% of the terminal passengers served by this
	airport were domestic passengers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Morelia International Airport serves the city of Morelia and ten other municipalities in the immediate
	vicinity. The city of Morelia is the capital of the state of Michoacan, which has a population of approximately 4.4&nbsp;million according to the Mexican National Population Council. Michoacan&#146;s principal industry is agriculture, and it has a
	developing eco-tourism industry (primarily due to the seasonal presence of monarch butterflies).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of six airlines operate at the
	airport; the principal ones are Volaris, Aerom&eacute;xico Group, American and United. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to eight&nbsp;destinations. Of these destinations, Tijuana, Chicago Midway and Mexico City are the most
	popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Morelia International Airport operates 24&nbsp;hours a day. The airport has one runway with a length of 3,400&nbsp;meters and a
	single main terminal building. The runway capacity at this airport is twelve air traffic movements per hour. The airport has four gates and eight remote boarding positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	During 2013, we completed construction on the arrivals area to expand it by 500&nbsp;square meters. The expansion included the addition of two
	new baggage claim belts and a re-organization of the customs and immigration facilities. In 2016, we expect to open two new convenience stores directly operated by us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Los Mochis International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Los Mochis International Airport is our eleventh most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic, tenth in terms of air traffic
	movements and eleventh in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Los Mochis International Airport was the thirty-seventh busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic,
	according to the SCT. In 2015, it served 290.9&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 1.1% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 98.3% of the terminal passengers served were
	domestic passengers. Because the airport&#146;s passengers are predominantly domestic, the airport&#146;s passenger traffic and results of operations are affected to a greater extent by Mexican economic conditions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Los Mochis International Airport serves the city of Los Mochis, in the Pacific coastal state of Sinaloa, an important agricultural state. The
	area&#146;s sport fishing and hunting attract both Mexican and foreign visitors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of five airlines operate at the airport:
	Aerom&eacute;xico Group, Volaris, Aeromar, Aerocalafia and TAR Aerol&iacute;neas. Airlines operating at this airport provide service to six destinations, of which Mexico City, Tijuana and Guadalajara are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Los Mochis International Airport operates fourteen hours daily between 7:00&nbsp;a.m. and 9:00&nbsp;p.m. However, it is equipped to operate
	24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we are authorized to charge double our
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	66
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage72"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	regular passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway measuring 2,000&nbsp;meters in length as well as a single main
	commercial terminal. The runway capacity at this airport is sixteen air traffic movements per hour. The airport has three gates and four remote boarding positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Manzanillo International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Manzanillo International Airport is our twelfth most important Mexican airport in terms of passenger traffic and air traffic movements and
	twelfth in terms of contribution to the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. In 2015, Manzanillo International Airport was the forty-first busiest airport in Mexico in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic according to the
	SCT. During 2015, the airport served 194.4&nbsp;thousand terminal passengers, accounting for approximately 0.7% of our Mexican airports&#146; terminal passenger traffic. During 2015, approximately 52.5% of the terminal passengers served were
	domestic passengers and 47.5% were international passengers. In October 2015, Hurricane Patricia caused the airport to suspend commercial operations for one and a half days, during which the airport sustained minimal damage. This damage was quickly
	repaired. No damage occurred to hotels in this area, and tourism was not materially affected.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Manzanillo International Airport serves the
	city of Manzanillo and six surrounding municipalities in the small Pacific coastal state of Colima. The city is located on the coast approximately 230 kilometers southeast of Puerto Vallarta and 520&nbsp;kilometers northwest of Acapulco. The airport
	serves primarily tourists visiting coastal resorts in Colima and neighboring Jalisco. In recent years, passenger traffic at Manzanillo International Airport has remained stable despite the increased popularity of Puerto Vallarta and other tourist
	destinations due to a decline in investments in the tourism sector in Manzanillo.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of nine airlines operate at this airport; the
	principal ones are Aerom&eacute;xico Group, Alaska and WestJet. Some of the other airlines operate only during the high tourist season (November to April). The principal destinations served by airlines at this airport are Mexico City, Los Angeles
	and Calgary.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Manzanillo International Airport operates twelve hours daily between 8:00&nbsp;a.m. and 8:00&nbsp;p.m. However, it is
	equipped to operate 24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary, and we double our passenger charges and fees for aeronautical services provided outside normal business hours. The airport has one runway measuring 2,200&nbsp;meters. The runway capacity at this
	airport is sixteen air traffic movements per hour. The airport has four gates and five remote boarding positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We plan to continue our
	expansion of commercial areas by opening two more directly operated convenience stores in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Newly Acquired Airport
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In April 2015, we acquired a 100% stake in our Spanish subsidiary, DCA. DCA holds a 74.5% stake in MBJA, the entity that operates Montego Bay
	International Airport in Jamaica. As a result of our acquisition of DCA in April 2015, our summary consolidated financial and operating information for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 includes the consolidation of MBJA&#146;s financial
	and operating information for the period from April&nbsp;1 to December&nbsp;31, 2015. Therefore, financial and operating information related to the Montego Bay airport for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 may not be directly comparable
	with financial and operating information for our Mexican airports for 2015 or for the Montego Bay airport for prior fiscal years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Montego Bay
	International Airport
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Montego Bay International Airport, located in the town of Montego Bay on the northwest coast of the island
	of Jamaica, is Jamaica&#146;s main airport. In 2015, the Montego Bay airport served 3.7&nbsp;million
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	67
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage73"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	terminal passengers, making it the third busiest airport in the Caribbean region (excluding Cuba) in terms of commercial aviation passenger traffic, according to Airports Council International.
	From April&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2015 (when we began to consolidate MBJA&#146;s financial and operating information) to December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, the airport served 2.7&nbsp;million terminal passengers. In 2015, 99.7% of the terminal passengers served
	were international passengers. Of the total passengers in 2015, 67.0% came from the United States, 18.6% came from Canada and 12.3% came from Europe.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Montego Bay International Airport serves as the primary gateway for international air travel to Jamaica, a major international tourist
	destination, by facilitating the transit of more than 71% of the tourists arriving on the island. The town of Montego Bay is in the geographical center of the tourist corridor between the coastal resort areas of Negril and Ocho Rios where 90.3% of
	the island&#146;s hotel capacity is located, according to the Jamaican Tourist Board. In recent years, passenger traffic at Montego Bay International Airport has grown despite the increased traffic overall at the Kingston airport, which services
	mostly business and other traffic. In recent years, the Jamaican government has discussed plans to build a third international commercial airport, most likely on the southern coast at Vernamfield to meet the long-term requirements for the growth of
	air transport. We do not expect the Kingston airport&#146;s traffic growth to be a major factor in the Montego Bay airport concession&#146;s growth, as the airports serve different demands, nor do we expect the Jamaican government&#146;s Vernamfield
	airport plan to be executed within the next three years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A total of eighteen international airlines operate at the airport; the principal
	airlines are American, Delta, JetBlue and Southwest. Airlines at this airport provide service from 20 cities to Jamaica. Of these, Toronto, New York and Atlanta are the most popular.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Montego Bay International Airport operates eighteen hours daily between 6&nbsp;a.m. and 12&nbsp;midnight. However, it is equipped to operate
	24&nbsp;hours daily if necessary. The airport has one runway measuring 2,662&nbsp;meters. The runway capacity at this airport is 33 air traffic movements per hour. The airport also has an ILS that assists pilots in poor weather. The airport&#146;s
	facilities include a main commercial terminal with a large parking facility and a general aviation building. The airport&#146;s main commercial terminal has a total area of approximately 6,000&nbsp;square meters, as well as parking facilities
	consisting of an additional 5,657&nbsp;square meters. The general aviation building has an additional area of 300&nbsp;square meters. The commercial terminal has 17 gates and 5 remote parking positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following table sets forth revenues, passenger traffic and air traffic movement data for the Montego Bay airport from April&nbsp;1 to
	December&nbsp;31, 2015:
</P>

</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the period between April&nbsp;1, 2015 and December&nbsp;31, 2015, approximately
	4.8&nbsp;thousand metric tons of cargo was transported through the airport.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Third parties operate a total of seven lounges in the Montego
	Bay airport: five hotel lounges and one general lounge in the arrivals area and one general lounge in the departures area. In 2015, we expanded the departures-area general lounge by 283.3 square meters.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Non-Airport Subsidiaries
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Although we are
	a holding company that has subsidiaries operating each of our thirteen airports, we also have three employee service company subsidiaries. The employee service companies provide part of the labor force that works in our airports but do not directly
	employ any personnel. Our employee service companies are (i)&nbsp;Servicios a la Infraestructura Aeroportuaria del Pac&iacute;fico, S.A. de C.V. (&#147;SIAP&#148;), (ii)&nbsp;Corporativo de Servicios Aeroportuarios, S.A. de C.V. (&#147;CORSA&#148;),
	and (iii)&nbsp;Puerta Cero Parking, S.A. de C.V. (&#147;PCP&#148;). Additionally, in 2013, we established a nonprofit company named Fundaci&oacute;n Grupo Aeroportuario del Pac&iacute;fico, A.C. (&#147;Fundaci&oacute;n GAP&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	SIAP
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	SIAP was incorporated as a
	subsidiary in June&nbsp;1998 to provide technical assistance and corporate services to our airport operating subsidiaries. SIAP was set up as part of the Mexican government&#146;s privatization plan for the airports operated by us. SIAP invoices our
	airports for three types of services:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
