	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for our six other Mexican airports increased 42.2%, or Ps.190.1&nbsp;million,
	from the Ps.450.0&nbsp;million recorded in 2014 to Ps.640.1&nbsp;million in 2015. This increase was primarily due to a 1246.5% or Ps.176.6&nbsp;million increase in the cost of improvements to concession assets from Ps.14.2&nbsp;million in 2014 to
	Ps.190.8&nbsp;million in 2015. Additionally, the cost of services increased Ps.37.0&nbsp;million, and depreciation and amortization increased Ps.4.3&nbsp;million. Operating costs increased 3.1%, or Ps.13.5&nbsp;million, without including
	improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income increased 47.9%, or Ps.1.3&nbsp;billion, from Ps.2.8&nbsp;billion in 2014 to Ps.4.1&nbsp;billion in 2015. This increase was
	due to higher revenue in 2015 and the consolidation of MBJA, (which contributed Ps.341.3 million), which was partially offset by increases in expenses. Our operating margin increased 50 basis points, from 49.9% in 2014 to 50.4% in 2015 (taking into
	account only the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues, the operating margin increased 380&nbsp;basis points in 2015, from 52.5% to 56.3%).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating margin is calculated by dividing income from operations at each airport by total revenues for that airport. Historically, our most
	profitable airports have been our Guadalajara, Los Cabos and Puerto Vallarta airports, which handle the majority of our international passengers. Historically, operating margins at our Tijuana airport have been lower than at our other principal
	airports because the maximum rates applicable to aeronautical services provided at our Tijuana airport are lower than those applicable to our other principal airports. This results from the amortization of our concession relative to the level of
	revenues being much higher at our Tijuana airport than at our other principal airports due to the fact that the original concession value assigned to the Tijuana airport was proportionately higher.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating Income by Airport
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating
	income for the Guadalajara airport increased by 15.3%, or Ps.179.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.1.2&nbsp;billion in 2014 to Ps.1.4&nbsp;billion in 2015, mainly due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues of Ps.280.3&nbsp;million.
	Additionally, operating costs increased Ps.32.1&nbsp;million and depreciation and amortization increased Ps.18.8&nbsp;million. The operating margin increased 260&nbsp;basis points, from 57.1% to 59.7% (operating margin increased 10&nbsp;basis
	points, from 63.1% to 63.2%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the
	Tijuana airport increased by 36.4%, or Ps.128.9&nbsp;million, from Ps.354.2&nbsp;million in 2014 to Ps.483.1 million in 2015, primarily due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues as a result of an increase in passenger traffic.
	The operating margin decreased 680&nbsp;basis points from 48.0% to 41.2% (operating margin increased&nbsp;580 basis points to 54.1% from 48.3%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Los Cabos airport increased by 29.0%, or Ps.149.1&nbsp;million, from Ps.514.0&nbsp;million in 2014 to
	Ps.663.1&nbsp;million in 2015, primarily due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin increased 90&nbsp;basis points from 52.6% to 53.5% (operating margin increased 380&nbsp;basis points, to 59.0% from
	55.2%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Montego Bay airport was
	for Ps.341.3 million for the period from April&nbsp;1 through December&nbsp;31, 2015, primarily due to aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues, which were greater than the operating costs. The operating margin was 34.3%, taking into account the
	sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Puerto Vallarta airport increased by 44.7%, or
	Ps.178.2&nbsp;million, from Ps.398.5&nbsp;million in 2014 to Ps.576.7&nbsp;million in 2015, mainly due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	128
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	revenues as a result of the increase in passenger traffic greater than the corresponding increase in operating costs. The operating margin increased 610&nbsp;basis points from 52.4% to 58.5%
	(operating margin increased 750&nbsp;basis points to 61.0% from 53.5%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Guanajuato airport increased 55.2%, or Ps.73.0&nbsp;million, from Ps.132.2&nbsp;million in 2014 to
	Ps.205.2&nbsp;million in 2015, primarily due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin increased 480&nbsp;basis points from 50.0% to 54.8% (operating margin increased 890&nbsp;basis points from 50.3% to
	59.2%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Hermosillo airport
	increased by 21.7%, or Ps.19.7&nbsp;million, from Ps.90.7&nbsp;million in 2014 to Ps.110.3&nbsp;million in 2015, primarily due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin decreased 360&nbsp;basis points from
	38.5% to 34.9% (operating margin increased 300&nbsp;basis points from 39.6% to 42.6%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for our six other Mexican airports increased 73.4%, or Ps.49.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.67.8&nbsp;million in 2014 to
	Ps.117.6&nbsp;million in 2015. The change in operating income was primarily due to a higher percentage increase in the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues as compared to our fixed costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Finance Income (Cost)
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our
	financial cost increased by Ps.448.8&nbsp;million in 2015 with respect to 2014, from an expense of Ps.8.0 million in 2014 to an expense of Ps.456.8&nbsp;million in 2015. This increase was mainly due to the foreign exchange rate loss of Ps.344.3
	million in 2015 regarding 2014, from an income of Ps.7.2 million in 2014 to an expense of Ps.337.1 million in 2015, as a result of a peso depreciation from Ps.14.71 per U.S. dollar at December&nbsp;31, 2014 to Ps.17.20 per U.S. dollar at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, derived from the U.S.$191.0&nbsp;million U.S. dollar-denominated loan obtained in connection with the acquisition of DCA, which was partially offset by the exchange rate gain of Ps.35.9 million in 2015. The effect of the
	foreign exchange rate loss was partially offset by the recognition of Ps.482.4&nbsp;million in revenues from currency translation effects in 2015, recognized within other comprehensive income, in accordance with applicable norms. Additionally, we
	incurred the following financial expenses: (i)&nbsp;Ps.138.9&nbsp;million in interest expense paid on loans for capital investments in Mexico; (ii)&nbsp;Ps.36.2&nbsp;million in financing interest expenses related to MBJA&#146;s debt and
	(iii)&nbsp;Ps.23.4 financing interest expenses paid for the acquisition of DCA. These expenses were partially offset by an increase in interest income of Ps.80.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As compared with
	2014, income taxes increased by Ps.332.7&nbsp;million, from Ps.514.6&nbsp;million in 2014 to Ps.847.3&nbsp;million in 2015. MBJA&#146;s income tax expense was Ps.74.1&nbsp;million, while the Mexican airports&#146; current tax increased by Ps.195.4
	million and deferred tax decreased by Ps.63.2 million due to a 2.1% inflation rate in 2015 as compared to a 4.1% inflation rate in 2014. Income taxes for 2015 principally consisted of the following: (i)&nbsp;current income tax expense for the year
	of Ps.1,030.0&nbsp;million, an increase of Ps.269.5&nbsp;million from 2014 to 2015; and (ii)&nbsp;a deferred income tax benefit decrease from Ps.245.9&nbsp;million in 2014 to Ps.182.7&nbsp;million in 2015. Our effective tax rate increased from 19%
	in 2014 to 23% in 2015.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Net Income and Comprehensive Income Attributable to Controlling Interest
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Net income and comprehensive income increased by 45.1%, or Ps.1.01 billion, from Ps.2.24 billion in 2014 to Ps.3.25 billion in 2015, mainly due
	to a Ps.1,323.5 million increase in operating income comprising a Ps.792.3 million increase in our Mexican airports&#146; operating income, a Ps.341.5 million increase from the consolidation of the Montego Bay airport and a Ps.189.7 increase due to
	bargain purchase gain from the acquisition of DCA. This effect was offset by a Ps.269.5 million increase in income taxes and a $63.2 million decrease in deferred tax. Our net margin decreased from 40.4% in 2014 to 34.2% in 2015 (taking into account
	only aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues, net margin decreased to 38.1% from 42.6%).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Statement of Financial Position
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The consolidation of DCA had a positive impact on the following items in the Company&#146;s financial statements as of December&nbsp;31, 2015:
	cash and cash equivalents of Ps.439.0&nbsp;million, trade accounts receivable of Ps.80.8&nbsp;million, equipment and machinery of Ps.413.7&nbsp;million, improvements to concession assets of Ps.1,996.0&nbsp;million, and airport concessions of
	Ps.2,912.9&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total liabilities increased by Ps.6,317.2&nbsp;million compared to the same period in 2014. This increase was
	primarily due to (i)&nbsp;the U.S.$191.0&nbsp;million (Ps.3,286.4&nbsp;million) bridge loan obtained for the acquisition of 100% of DCA&#146;s shares, (ii)&nbsp;a Ps.850.0 million increase in capital market debt for capital expenditures financing,
	(iii)&nbsp;MBJA financial debt of Ps.663.9&nbsp;million, (iv)&nbsp;deferred tax liabilities of Ps.818.8&nbsp;million due to the Montego Bay airport&#146;s concession assets, (v)&nbsp;accounts payable of Ps.336.6&nbsp;million, (vi)&nbsp;deposits
	received in guarantee of Ps.128.3 million, (vii)&nbsp;income taxes payable of Ps.99.4 million and (viii)&nbsp;concession taxes payable of Ps.79.1 million, among other liabilities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Results of Operations for the Year ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014 Compared to the Year Ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Revenues
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total revenues for 2014
	increased 6.1%, from Ps.5,227.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.5,546.2&nbsp;million in 2014, due to an increase of Ps.309.1&nbsp;million in aeronautical services revenues and an increase of Ps.168.1&nbsp;million in non-aeronautical services revenues.
	This was partially offset by a Ps.158.9&nbsp;million decrease in revenues from improvements to concession assets as a result of the committed investments outlined in our Master Development Programs, which for 2014 were less than the corresponding
	amounts in 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Aeronautical Services Revenues
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Aeronautical services revenues increased 8.5%, from Ps.3,616.6&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.3, 925.7&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a
	6.7% increase in passenger traffic compared to 2013, a 4.24% increase in the Mexican PPI, excluding petroleum, and a 2.05% increase in specific tariffs as of May&nbsp;2,&nbsp;2014. Revenues from passenger charges increased 9.7% or
	Ps.298.0&nbsp;million, primarily driven by a 6.7% increase in passengers that paid passenger charges and the increase in specific tariffs as of May&nbsp;2,&nbsp;2014. During 2014, revenues from aircraft landing and parking fees increased 2.3%, or
	Ps.7.6&nbsp;million, while revenues from the leasing of spaces to airlines for ticket counter, airport security and back office space and complementary services increased 1.7%, or Ps.3.5&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	130
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage137"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Non-Aeronautical Services Revenues
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Non-aeronautical services revenues for 2014 increased Ps.168.1&nbsp;million, or 14.4%, from Ps.1,170.5&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.1,338.5&nbsp;million in 2014. The primary factor influencing the change in non-aeronautical revenues from 2013 to 2014 was the Ps.119.5&nbsp;million increase in businesses operated by us, mainly driven by car parking charges, revenues related to
	the operation of the baggage screening systems, VIP lounges, convenience stores and advertising. In addition, revenues from businesses operated by third parties increased by Ps.48.6&nbsp;million, principally due to increases in revenues from the
	leasing of space, car rentals, food and beverage operations, retail operations, duty-free operations and ground transportation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Revenues from
	Improvements to Concession Assets
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Revenues from improvements to concession assets in 2014 decreased Ps.158.9&nbsp;million, or 36.0%,
	from Ps.440.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.281.9&nbsp;million in 2014. The main factor that determines the change in revenues from improvements to concession assets from 2013 to 2014 was a decrease in our commitments under the Master Development
	Programs for 2014. During 2014, the main commitments of improvements to concession assets included: (i)&nbsp;the expansion of the terminals at the Guadalajara, La Paz, Mexicali and Los Cabos airports and (ii)&nbsp;the adaptation of the Tijuana
	terminal for the cross-border bridge and the construction of the bridge.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Revenues by Airport
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Total revenues at most of our airports increased, mainly due to the increase in aeronautical services revenues.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Guadalajara airport, revenues increased by 6.1% or Ps.117.7&nbsp;million, from Ps.1,935.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.2,053.4&nbsp;million in 2014 (revenues increased 9.5%, or Ps.162.0&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services). Aeronautical revenues increased 9.1% or Ps.119.1&nbsp;million, from
	Ps.1,313.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.1,432.5&nbsp;million in 2014, due to a Ps.113.8&nbsp;million or 10.3% increase in passenger charges driven by a 7.2% increase in passenger traffic and a 2.05% increase in tariffs due to inflation.
	Non-aeronautical revenues increased 11.2% or Ps.42.9&nbsp;million, from Ps.383.1&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.426.0&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a Ps.26.3&nbsp;million increase in revenues from businesses operated by third parties, such as
	leasing of space, food and beverage operations, car rentals and retail operations. Revenues from business lines operated by us increased Ps.10.6&nbsp;million, principally as a result of increased revenues related to the operation of the baggage
	screening systems, advertising and VIP lounges. Revenues from improvements to concession assets decreased Ps.44.3&nbsp;million (an increase of 9.5% taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Tijuana airport, revenues increased by 6.6% or Ps.45.5&nbsp;million, from Ps.692.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.737.6&nbsp;million in
	2014, mainly due to a 4.2% or Ps.22.7&nbsp;million increase in aeronautical revenues, from Ps.546.3&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.569.0&nbsp;million in 2014 (revenues increased 7.5% taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and
	non-aeronautical services). This increase was due to an increase in passenger charges of Ps.24.0&nbsp;million as well as in revenues from landing and aircraft parking charges, which together increased Ps.0.4&nbsp;million, and was offset by a
	decrease in airport security charges, leasing of space to airlines and complementary services, which together decreased Ps.1.7 million. Non-aeronautical revenues increased by 20.7% or Ps.28.2&nbsp;million, from Ps.136.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.164.6&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to an increase of Ps.22.7&nbsp;million from business lines operated by us, including car parking, VIP lounges, advertising and operation of the baggage screening systems. In addition, revenues from
	business lines operated by third parties increased Ps.5.5&nbsp;million, including from leasing of space, food and beverage operations, retail operations and car rentals and leasing. Revenues from improvements to concession assets decreased
	Ps.5.4&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	131
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage138"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Los Cabos airport, revenues increased by 2.5% or Ps.24.0&nbsp;million, from
	Ps.953.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.977.4&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to an increase of Ps.32.2&nbsp;million in revenues from improvements to concession assets. This increase, in turn, was offset by the impact of Hurricane Odile, which caused
	the airport to suspend commercial operations for 18&nbsp;days and subsequently affected the number of passengers flying to the area (revenues decreased 0.9%, or Ps.8.2&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and
	non-aeronautical services). Aeronautical revenues decreased by 0.7% or Ps.4.3&nbsp;million, from Ps.604.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.599.9&nbsp;million in 2014, due to decreases in landing charges, aircraft parking charges, leasing of space to
	airlines and airport security charges totaling Ps.4.4&nbsp;million, mainly due to the impact of Hurricane Odile. Non-aeronautical revenues decreased by 1.2% or Ps.3.9&nbsp;million, from Ps.335.3&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.331.5&nbsp;million in 2014,
	primarily due to a Ps.3.0&nbsp;million decrease in revenues from business lines operated by us, including convenience stores, revenues related to the operation of the baggage screening systems, advertising and VIP lounges, as well as a Ps.0.8
	million decrease in revenues from business lines operated by third parties, including leasing of space, food and beverage operations, car rentals, leasing of space to timeshare developers and duty-free operations. These decreases were mainly due to
	the temporary closure of the airport during and after Hurricane Odile.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Puerto Vallarta airport, revenues increased by 16.8% or
	Ps.109.5&nbsp;million, from Ps.650.6&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.760.2&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to a 18.6% or Ps.85.5&nbsp;million increase in aeronautical revenues, from Ps.460.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.545.9&nbsp;million in 2014
	(revenues increased by 18.9%, or Ps.118.7&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services). This increase was due to an increase in passenger charges of Ps.81.4&nbsp;million, itself caused by a 2.8%
	increase in passenger traffic and a 2.05% increase in tariffs due to inflation, whereas revenues from landing airport security charges and aircraft parking charges increased a combined Ps.4.0&nbsp;million. Non-aeronautical revenues increased by
	19.9%, or Ps.33.2&nbsp;million, from Ps.166.5&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.199.7&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a Ps.14.5&nbsp;million increase in revenues from businesses operated by third parties, including retail operations, leasing of
	space to timeshare developers and other commercial spaces, as well as an increase in revenues from business lines operated by us of Ps.22.4&nbsp;million, including revenues related to the operation of the baggage screening systems, convenience
	stores and VIP lounges. The increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues was partially offset by a decrease of Ps.9.1&nbsp;million in revenues from improvements to concession assets in 2014, as compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Hermosillo airport, revenues increased by 9.9% or Ps.21.3&nbsp;million, from Ps.214.0&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.235.3&nbsp;million in
	2014, primarily due to a 36.8% increase in non-aeronautical revenues (revenues increased 6.9%, or Ps.14.7&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services). Aeronautical revenues increased by 0.01% or
	Ps.0.01&nbsp;million, from Ps.173.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.173.8&nbsp;million in 2014. Non-aeronautical revenues increased by 36.8% or Ps.14.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.40.1&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.54.9&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a
	Ps.12.9&nbsp;million increase in revenues from business lines operated by us related to the operation of the baggage screening systems, advertising, conveniences store and VIP lounges, as well as due to a Ps.1.7&nbsp;million increase in revenues
	from business lines operated by third parties, primarily resulting from the leasing of space, food and beverage operations, car rentals, other commercial revenues and financial services. Revenues from improvements to concession assets increased by
	Ps.6.5&nbsp;million in 2014, as compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Guanajuato airport, revenues increased by 25.4% or Ps.53.5&nbsp;million, from
	Ps.210.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.264.3&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to a 24.2%, or Ps.39.5&nbsp;million, increase in aeronautical revenues, from Ps.163.0&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.202.5&nbsp;million in 2014 (revenues increased 29.0%, or
	Ps.59.0&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services). Aeronautical revenues increased by 24.2% from Ps.163.0&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.202.5&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to a 22.4% increase in
	passenger traffic and a 2.05% increase in tariffs related to inflation. Non-aeronautical revenues increased by 47.9% or Ps.19.5&nbsp;million, from Ps.40.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.60.3&nbsp;million in 2014. This increase is a result of a
	Ps.14.2&nbsp;million increase in revenues from businesses
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	132
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage139"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	operated by us, including increases in advertising, car parking charges and revenues related to the operation of the baggage screening systems, as well as a Ps.5.4&nbsp;million increase in
	revenues from businesses operated by third parties, including the leasing of space, car rentals and communications services. The increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues was partially offset by a decrease of Ps.5.5&nbsp;million in
	revenues from improvements to concession assets in 2014, as compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Revenues at our other six Mexican airports decreased by
	9.3% or Ps.53.2&nbsp;million, from Ps.571.0&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.517.9&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to a decrease of 90.4%, or Ps.133.3&nbsp;million, from Ps.147.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.14.2&nbsp;million in 2014, in revenues from
	improvements to concession assets (revenues increased 18.9%, or Ps.80.1&nbsp;million, taking into account only revenues from aeronautical and non-aeronautical services). Aeronautical revenues at these airports increased by 13.2% or
	Ps.46.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.355.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.402.2&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to a 11.3% increase in passenger traffic and a 2.05% increase in tariffs, due to inflation. Non-aeronautical revenues increased by 48.8% or
	Ps.33.3&nbsp;million, from Ps.68.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.101.5&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a Ps.30.0 million increase in revenues from businesses operated by us, including increases in advertising, car parking charges and revenues
	related to the operation of the baggage screening systems, as well as a Ps.3.3&nbsp;million increase in revenues from businesses operated by third parties, including the leasing of space, car rentals and communications services.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Costs
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs
	at our Mexican airports decreased by Ps.73.6&nbsp;million, or 2.6%, mainly due to the 36.0% decrease in the cost of improvements to concession assets described below. The decrease in cost of improvements to concession assets was mostly offset by a
	Ps.32.6&nbsp;million, or 2.9%, increase in cost of services and a Ps.42.0 million, or 4.8%, increase in depreciation and amortization described below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of Services
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Cost of services, which
	is composed of employee costs, maintenance, safety, security, insurance, utilities and other expenses, increased by Ps.32.6&nbsp;million, or 2.9%, from Ps.1.1&nbsp;billion in 2013 to Ps.1.2&nbsp;billion in 2014. Maintenance expenses increased 11.7%,
	or Ps.23.5&nbsp;million, mainly due to routine maintenance on runways, security equipment, machinery and equipment, in addition to major maintenance undertaken in certain operational areas. Safety, security and insurance expenses increased 11.0%, or
	Ps.19.2&nbsp;million, mainly due to an increase in security. Utility expenses increased 4.2%, or Ps.5.9&nbsp;million, mainly due to an increase in electricity rates and higher consumption of electricity as a result of the expansion of our terminals
	and the operation of new baggage screening system equipment. Employee costs increased 0.8%, or Ps.2.9 million. This increase was partially offset by a decrease of 8.5%, or Ps.18.9&nbsp;million, in other costs, mainly due to decreases in professional
	fees related to legal defense and corporate consulting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The main airport that contributed to the increase in the cost of services for
	2014 was the Puerto Vallarta airport. The cost of services at our Puerto Vallarta airport increased from Ps.141.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.152.8&nbsp;million in 2014, or 7.7%, mainly as a result of the opening of the new convenience stores.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Technical Assistance Fee
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The technical
	assistance fee increased 13.3%, or Ps.22.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.171.5&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.194.2&nbsp;million in 2014. This increase was mainly due to an increase in our consolidated income from operations, which is used to calculate this
	fee. See &#147;Item&nbsp;4,
<I>
	Information on the Company &#150; History and Development of the Company &#150; Investment by AMP.
</I>
	&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	133
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage140"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Concession Tax
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As a result of increased revenues (excluding revenues from improvements to concession assets as they do not form part of income for purposes of
	the government concession tax), government concession taxes increased 10.0%, from Ps.237.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.261.6&nbsp;million in 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Depreciation and Amortization
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Depreciation and amortization increased 4.8%, or Ps.42.0&nbsp;million, from Ps.883.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.925.2&nbsp;million in 2014,
	mainly due to the growth in infrastructure resulting from our fulfillment of our Master Development Programs and our commitment to provide better services to our clients. The amortization of concessions did not fluctuate materially.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Cost of Improvements to Concession Assets
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Cost of improvements to concession assets in 2014 decreased Ps.158.9&nbsp;million, or 36.0%, from Ps.440.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.281.9&nbsp;million in 2014. The primary factor influencing the decrease in cost of improvements to concession assets from 2013 to 2014 was the change in amounts allocated in our Master Development Programs for 2014 as compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating Costs by Airport
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating
	costs for the Guadalajara airport were Ps.881.5&nbsp;million in 2014, a 0.3%, or Ps.2.6&nbsp;million, increase from the Ps.878.9&nbsp;million recorded in 2013. This increase was primarily due to a 9.2%, or Ps.37.2&nbsp;million, increase in the cost
	of services, mainly in utilities, safety, security and insurance and maintenance, as well as a Ps.9.7&nbsp;million increase in depreciation and amortization (operating costs increased Ps.46.9&nbsp;million, or 7.3%, without including the cost of
	improvements to concession assets). The increase was partially offset by a Ps.44.3&nbsp;million decrease in the cost of improvements to concession assets from Ps.239.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.194.9&nbsp;million in 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for the Tijuana airport increased Ps.15.9&nbsp;million, or 4.3%, to Ps.383.4&nbsp;million in 2014 from Ps.367.5&nbsp;million
	in 2013. This increase was due to a 7.5%, or Ps.17.1&nbsp;million, increase in the cost of operation mainly in utilities and safety, security and insurance, from Ps.227.2 million in 2013 to Ps 244.3&nbsp;million in 2014, and an increase of
	Ps.4.3&nbsp;million in depreciation and amortization. The increase was partially offset by a Ps.5.4&nbsp;million decrease in the cost of improvements to concession assets from Ps.9.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.4.0&nbsp;million in 2014. Operating
	costs increased 6.0%, or Ps.21.4&nbsp;million, without including improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for the Los Cabos
	airport increased 8.7%, or Ps.37.2&nbsp;million, to Ps.463.5&nbsp;million in 2014 from the Ps.426.3&nbsp;million recorded in 2013. This increase was mainly due to a 232.2%, or Ps.32.2&nbsp;million, increase in the cost of improvements to concession
	assets from Ps.13.9&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.46.1&nbsp;million in 2014 in addition to a Ps.22.0&nbsp;million increase in depreciation and amortization. This increase was partially offset by a Ps.17.0&nbsp;million increase in the cost of services,
	mainly due to remodeling costs for the terminal damaged by Hurricane Odile. Operating costs increased 1.2%, or Ps.5.0&nbsp;million, without including improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for the Puerto Vallarta airport increased 4.4%, or Ps.15.3&nbsp;million, to Ps.361.6&nbsp;million in 2014 from
	Ps.346.4&nbsp;million in 2013. This increase was primarily due to an 11.8%, or Ps.23.2&nbsp;million, increase in the cost of services, mainly due to an increase in the cost of supplies for convenience stores and maintenance cost. The increase was
	partially offset by a Ps.9.1&nbsp;million increase in the cost of improvements to concession assets. Operating costs decreased 7.6%, or Ps.24.4&nbsp;million, without including of improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for the Hermosillo airport increased 13.1%, or Ps.16.8&nbsp;million, to Ps.144.7&nbsp;million in 2014 from the
	Ps.127.9&nbsp;million recorded in 2013. This increase was due to an 8430.6% or
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	134
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage141"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Ps.6.6&nbsp;million increase in the cost of improvements to concession assets from Ps.0.1&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.6.6&nbsp;million in 2014. The cost of services increased Ps.9.7&nbsp;million,
	mainly in maintenance and the cost of supplies for convenience stores, and depreciation and amortization increased Ps.0.5&nbsp;million. Operating costs increased 8.0%, or Ps.10.2&nbsp;million, without including improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for the Guanajuato airport increased 2.7% or Ps.3.5&nbsp;million, from the Ps.128.7&nbsp;million recorded in 2013 to
	Ps.132.1&nbsp;million in 2014. This increase was primarily due to a 9.8% or Ps.7.8&nbsp;million increase in the cost of services, mainly in maintenance costs, as well as increase in the cost of supplies for convenience stores and professional
	services. The increase was partially offset by a Ps.5.5&nbsp;million increase in the cost of improvements to concession assets; from Ps.7.0&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.1.5&nbsp;million in 2014 (operating costs increased 7.4% or Ps.9.0&nbsp;million
	without including improvements to concession assets).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating costs for our six other airports decreased 18.1%, or
	Ps.99.4&nbsp;million, from the Ps.549.4&nbsp;million recorded in 2013 to Ps.450.0&nbsp;million in 2014. This decrease was primarily due to a 90.4% or Ps.133.3&nbsp;million increase in the cost of improvements to concession assets from
	Ps.147.4&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.14.2&nbsp;million in 2014. Additionally, the cost of services increased Ps.2.1&nbsp;million, and depreciation and amortization increased Ps.31.7&nbsp;million. Operating costs increased 8.4%, or
	Ps.33.8&nbsp;million, without including improvements to concession assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Income
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income increased 16.5%, or Ps.391.9&nbsp;million, from Ps.2.4&nbsp;billion in 2013 to Ps.2.8&nbsp;billion in 2014. This increase was
	due to higher revenue in 2014, which was partially offset by increases in expenses. Our operating margin increased 446 basis points, from 45.4% in 2013 to 49.9% in 2014 (taking into account only the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues,
	the operating margin increased 432&nbsp;basis points in 2014, from 49.6% to 52.5%).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating margin is calculated by dividing income
	from operations at each airport by total revenues for that airport. Historically, our most profitable airports have been our Guadalajara, Los Cabos and Puerto Vallarta airports, which handle the majority of our international passengers. Operating
	margins at our Tijuana airport historically have been lower than at our other principal airports because the maximum rates applicable to aeronautical services provided at our Tijuana airport are lower than those applicable to our other principal
	airports. This results from the amortization of our concession relative to the level of revenues being much higher at our Tijuana airport than at our other principal airports due to the fact that the original concession value assigned to the Tijuana
	airport was proportionately higher.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Operating Income by Airport
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Guadalajara airport increased by 10.9%, or Ps.115.1&nbsp;million, from Ps.1,056.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.1,171.9&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues of Ps.162.0&nbsp;million. Additionally, operating costs increased Ps.37.2&nbsp;million and depreciation and amortization increased
	Ps.9.7&nbsp;million. The operating margin increased 248&nbsp;basis points, from 54.6% to 57.1% (operating margin increased 76&nbsp;basis points, from 62.3% to 63.1%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Tijuana airport increased by 9.1%, or Ps.29.5&nbsp;million, from Ps.324.7&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.354.2
	million in 2014, primarily due to a greater increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues (as a result of an increase in passenger traffic) than the corresponding increase in operating costs. The operating margin increased 111&nbsp;basis
	points from 46.9% to 48.0% (operating margin increased&nbsp;73 basis points to 47.6% from 48.3%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	135
</P>

<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Los Cabos airport decreased by 2.5%, or Ps.13.2&nbsp;million, from
	Ps.527.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.514.0&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to a decrease in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin decreased 271&nbsp;basis points from 55.3% to 52.6% (operating margin decreased
	92&nbsp;basis points, to 56.1% from 55.2%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating
	income for the Puerto Vallarta airport increased by 31.0%, or Ps.94.2&nbsp;million, from Ps.304.3&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.398.5&nbsp;million in 2014, mainly due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues as a result of the
	increase in passenger traffic greater than the corresponding increase in operating costs. The operating margin increased 566&nbsp;basis points from 46.8% to 52.4% (operating margin increased 492&nbsp;basis points to 48.6% from 53.5%, taking into
	account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Hermosillo airport increased by 5.2%, or
	Ps.4.5&nbsp;million, from Ps.86.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.90.7&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to an increase in the aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin decreased 173&nbsp;basis points from 40.3% to 38.5%
	(operating margin decreased 63&nbsp;basis points from 40.3% to 39.6%, taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for the Guanajuato airport increased by 60.9%, or Ps.50.0&nbsp;million, from Ps.82.2&nbsp;million in 2013 to
	Ps.132.2&nbsp;million in 2014, primarily due to an increase in aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues. The operating margin increased 1,104&nbsp;basis points from 38.9% to 50.0% (operating margin increased 999&nbsp;basis points from 40.3% to
	50.3% taking into account the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical revenues only).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Operating income for our six other airports
	increased by 214.2%, or Ps.46.3&nbsp;million, from Ps.21.6&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.67.8&nbsp;million in 2014. The change in operating income was primarily due to a higher percentage increase in the sum of aeronautical and non-aeronautical
	revenues as compared to our fixed costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Finance Income (Cost)
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our finance cost decreased by Ps.43.2&nbsp;million in 2014 with respect to 2013, from an expense of Ps.51.2 million in 2013 to an expense of
	Ps.8.0&nbsp;million in 2014. Interest income went from an expense of Ps.54.9 million in 2013 to an expense of Ps.15.2&nbsp;million in 2014, which represented a net change of Ps.39.8 million, due to: (i)&nbsp;a decrease of Ps.49.8&nbsp;million in the
	capitalization of interest on bank loans in 2014; (ii)&nbsp;a Ps.23.7&nbsp;million increase in the price of Pemex bonds, classified as Fair Value Through Profit or Loss (FVTPL); and (iii)&nbsp;exchange rate gains increasing from a gain of
	Ps.3.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to a gain of Ps.7.2&nbsp;million in 2014, resulting in a net increase of Ps.3.4&nbsp;million. This effect occurred due to the 12.9% devaluation of the Mexican peso against the U.S. dollar during 2014, while during 2013,
	the Mexican peso depreciated 0.4%. This increase was partially offset by a decrease of Ps.37.9&nbsp;million in interest gains due to lower interest rates and a lower average of cash and cash equivalents.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As compared with
	2013, income taxes increased by Ps.438.8&nbsp;million, from Ps.75.8&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.514.6&nbsp;million in 2014. Income taxes for 2014 principally consisted of the following: (i)&nbsp;current income tax expense for the year of
	Ps.760.5&nbsp;million, an increase of Ps.106.9&nbsp;million from 2013 to 2014 mainly due to an increase of 18.7% in income before taxes; and (ii)&nbsp;a deferred income tax benefit decrease from Ps.577.9&nbsp;million in 2013 to Ps.245.9&nbsp;million
	in 2014 associated primarily with (a)&nbsp;the 2014 Tax Reform&#146;s effects on the income tax rate (increased from 28% to 30%) and (b)&nbsp;the change in tax amortization rates applied over our concession and rights to use airport facilities in
	some of our airports, which generated a tax benefit of Ps.243.5&nbsp;million in 2013. Our effective tax rate increased from 3% in 2013 to 19% in 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Historically, our operations had been funded through cash flow from operations, and we did not incur any significant indebtedness until 2007.
	The cash flow generated from our operations has generally been used to fund operating costs and capital expenditures, including expenditures under our Master Development Programs, and the excess of our cash flow has been added to our accumulated
	cash balances. In 2014, we decided to modify our leverage strategy to rely more heavily on debt issuances on the Mexican capital markets while continuing to use working capital and resources expected to be generated from operations. On April&nbsp;1,
	2015, we consolidated MBJA&#146;s results of operations, including net debt in the amount of U.S.$21.4&nbsp;million. In our opinion, our working capital is sufficient for our present requirements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, 2014 and 2015, we had Ps.2.2&nbsp;billion, Ps.1.6&nbsp;billion and Ps.3.0&nbsp;billion, respectively, of
	cash and cash equivalents. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, we had Ps.410.4&nbsp;million of financial investments held for trading purposes and we recorded no financial investments held for trading purposes as of December&nbsp;31, 2014 and 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Cash Flows
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, we
	generated Ps.4.9&nbsp;billion from operating activities, principally reflecting income from operations after taking into consideration the effect of our non-monetary assets, such as depreciation and amortization. Income generated from operations was
	mainly used to make: (i)&nbsp;dividend payments of Ps.1.7 billion (Ps.956.5&nbsp;million on August&nbsp;21,&nbsp;2015 and Ps.788.4&nbsp;million on November&nbsp;4,&nbsp;2015); (ii)&nbsp;a capital distribution of Ps.1.4&nbsp;billion on May&nbsp;15,
	2015; (iii) payment of income taxes by Ps.930.7 million; and (iv) cost of debt by Ps.177.8 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2014, we generated
	Ps.3.5&nbsp;billion from operating activities, principally reflecting income from operations after taking into consideration the effect of our non-monetary assets, such as depreciation and amortization. Income generated from operations was mainly
	used to make: (i)&nbsp;dividend payments of Ps.1.6 billion (Ps.1.2&nbsp;billion on May&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2014 and Ps.397.5&nbsp;million on July&nbsp;4,&nbsp;2014); (ii)&nbsp;a capital distribution of Ps.1.5&nbsp;billion on May&nbsp;8, 2014;
	(iii)&nbsp;capital expenditures of approximately Ps.106.8&nbsp;million in machinery, equipment and improvements to our airport facilities; and (iv)&nbsp;share repurchases of approximately Ps.69.3&nbsp;million in shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2013, we generated Ps.3.0&nbsp;billion from operating activities, principally reflecting income from operations after taking into
	consideration the effect of our non-monetary assets, such as depreciation and amortization. Income generated from operations was mainly used to make: (i)&nbsp;dividend payments of Ps.1.2 billion (Ps.907.5&nbsp;million on April&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2013 and
	Ps.302.5&nbsp;million on November&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2013); (ii)&nbsp;capital expenditures of approximately Ps.192.7&nbsp;million in machinery, equipment and improvements to our airport facilities; and (iii)&nbsp;share repurchases of approximately
	Ps.276.7&nbsp;million in shares.
</P>

<I>
	Indebtedness
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we were in compliance with all covenants stipulated by these credit agreements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Indebtedness in Mexico
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	May&nbsp;26,&nbsp;2011 and June&nbsp;6, 2011, we entered into a Ps.1.0&nbsp;billion line of credit with HSBC and a Ps.551.4&nbsp;million line of credit with Banamex, respectively, represented by unsecured credit agreements with cross guarantees
	provided by the individual airports, for our Guadalajara, Puerto Vallarta, Los Cabos, Hermosillo and Guanajuato airports. These two lines served to finance working capital and capital investments previously committed pursuant to our Master
	Development Programs at these airports for the years 2011 and 2012. On November&nbsp;23, 2012 and April&nbsp;10, 2013, we contracted additional Ps.287.8&nbsp;million and Ps.459.4&nbsp;million loans with BBVA Bancomer for these airports in order to
	repay prior lines of credit with other banks. During the months of January and February 2015, we prepaid each of these loans in full.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On
	November&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2014, we opened a revolving credit line with Scotiabank for a total of Ps.1,741.0&nbsp;million to pre-pay prior bank loans. Credit taken under this line bore interest at the variable 28-day TIIE rate plus 57&nbsp;basis points,
	with a single payment of the principal 180 days after the disbursement and monthly interest payments. During the months of January and February 2015, we prepaid this line of credit in full.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In 2014, we decided to modify our leverage strategy to rely more heavily on debt issuances on the Mexican capital markets while
	continuing to use working capital and resources expected to be generated from operations. In 2014, we obtained new funds through a bank loan of Ps.1.4 billion for use in connection with our capital expenditures in 2014 and to pre-pay prior bank
	loans. On February&nbsp;20,&nbsp;2015, we made our debut issuance of long-term debt securities on the Mexican market for a total of Ps.2.6&nbsp;billion, the proceeds from which were used to repay in full our outstanding bank debt of
	Ps.1.7&nbsp;billion and to finance capital investments set forth in the Master Development Program for 2015. The long-term debt securities were issued in two tranches with the following terms: (i)&nbsp;eleven million five-year debt securities issued
	under the ticker symbol
<I>
	&#147;
</I>
	GAP 15&#148; at a nominal value of Ps.100 each, for a total value of Ps.1.1&nbsp;billion, on which interest will be payable every 28&nbsp;days at a variable rate of 28-day TIIE plus 24 basis points, and the
	principal will be payable at maturity on February&nbsp;14,&nbsp;2020; and (ii)&nbsp;fifteen million ten-year debt securities issued under the ticker symbol
<I>
	&#147;
</I>
	GAP 15-2&#148; at a nominal value of Ps.100 each, for a total value of
	Ps.1.5&nbsp;billion, on which interest will be payable every 182&nbsp;days at a fixed rate of 7.08%, and the principal will be payable at maturity on February&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2025.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In April 2015, we borrowed a total of U.S.$191.0 million through bridge loans with Scotiabank and BBVA Bancomer, with which we financed 100%
	of the acquisition of DCA. On May&nbsp;19, 2015, we signed two new credit agreements with Scotiabank for a total of U.S.$191.0 million at the variable one-month LIBOR rate plus 70 basis points for the refinancing of the bridge loans obtained in
	April 2015. On August&nbsp;19, 2015, we signed a new U.S.$95.0 million loan agreement with BBVA Bancomer, at the variable one-month LIBOR rate plus 60 basis points and due at maturity six months from disbursement, in order to prepay U.S.$95.0
	million of the loan obtained on May&nbsp;19, 2015 with Scotiabank for the acquisition of DCA. On September&nbsp;24, 2015, we signed two new credit agreements for the refinancing of the bridge loans obtained for the acquisition of DCA. The new loans,
	also from Scotiabank and BBVA Bancomer, amount to U.S.$191.0&nbsp;million and are due at maturity in five years. On January&nbsp;19 and February&nbsp;15, 2016, we paid off the bridge loans with Scotiabank and BBVA Bancomer for U.S.$96.0 million and
	U.S.$95.0 million, respectively. These loans were paid with funds obtained from new five-year loans obtained on the same respective dates with Scotiabank and BBVA Bancomer for U.S.$95.5 million each, at the variable one-month LIBOR rate plus 99 and
	105 basis points, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">

</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On January&nbsp;29, 2016, we issued another eleven million GAP 15 debt securities for a total
	value of Ps.1.1 billion. This issuance is the first reopening of the GAP 15 debt securities originally issued on February&nbsp;20, 2015, and has the same characteristics as the original issuance except for the issuance date and placement price. The
	proceeds from this issuance were allocated to finance investments set forth in the Company&#146;s Master Development Program for 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Indebtedness in
	Jamaica
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On September&nbsp;14, 2007, MBJA entered into a loan with the International Finance Corporation (&#147;IFC&#148;) for up to
	U.S.$20.0 million. The loan bears interest at a variable rate of 6-month LIBOR plus 392 basis points, with semi-annual principal and interest payments and final maturity in February 2019. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, the balance outstanding
	under this facility amounted to U.S.$11.8 million (Ps.203.4 million).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As part of the IFC loan transaction described above, MBJA entered
	into unsecured loans with its shareholder, Vantage, for U.S.$10.9 million and U.S.$0.5 million, in June 2007 and February 2009, respectively. The loans bear annual interest, payable semi-annually, at 14.0% and 8.0%, respectively, without fixed
	maturity, and are subject to prepayment restrictions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On December&nbsp;12, 2012, MBJA entered into a second loan with IFC for
	U.S.$13.5&nbsp;million. The loan bears interest at a variable rate of 6-month LIBOR plus 450 basis points, with semi-annual principal and interest payments and final maturity five years from each disbursement. As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, the
	balance outstanding under this facility amounted to U.S.$12.7 million (Ps.219.4 million).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Capital Expenditures
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2013, 2014 and 2015, we had total capital expenditures of Ps.686.3&nbsp;million,
	Ps.620.3&nbsp;million and Ps.1.1&nbsp;billion, respectively. During 2013, 2014 and 2015, 17.3%, 17.2% and 4.2%, respectively, of our capital expenditures were funded by cash flows from operations, while the remaining balance was funded with bank
	loans and long-term debt securities issued on the Mexican capital markets. We currently intend to fund the investments and working capital required by our business strategy through cash flows from operations and from the indebtedness described
	above.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Capital Expenditures in Mexico
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under the terms of our Mexican concessions, each of our Mexican subsidiary concession holders is required to present a Master Development
	Program for approval by the SCT every five years. Each Master Development Program includes investment commitments (including capital expenditures and improvements) applicable to us as the concession holder for the succeeding five-year period. Once
	approved by the SCT, these commitments become binding obligations under the terms of our Mexican concessions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In December&nbsp;2009, the
	SCT approved our Master Development Programs for each of our Mexican airports for the 2010 to 2014 period. This five-year program was in effect from January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2010 until December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014. In December&nbsp;2014, the SCT approved
	our Master Development Programs for each of our Mexican airports for the 2015 to 2019 period. This five-year program is in effect from January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2015 until December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2019.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The table below sets forth our historical capital expenditures in Mexico. Capital expenditures are calculated on a cash flow basis, meaning
	that capital expenditures are equal to those investments actually paid for by each airport during a given year and not including investments for which the airport made allocations but did not pay during the given year. The investments shown in the
	table below therefore reflect our expenditures actually paid for by our airports for the years indicated. In order to be compared
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	139
</P>

	the given year need to be added. For the 2013, 2014 and 2015, the total of our investments allocated but unpaid were Ps.135.4&nbsp;million, Ps.86.3&nbsp;million and Ps.221.2&nbsp;million, respectively.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2015, we spent Ps.1.1&nbsp;billion on capital expenditures in
	Mexico, primarily for expansion and remodeling of terminal buildings and improvements to runways and aprons at our Morelia, Guadalajara and Puerto Vallarta airports and acquisition of fire trucks at all airports. In 2014, we spent
	Ps.620.3&nbsp;million on capital expenditures, primarily for expansion and remodeling of terminal buildings and improvements to runways and aprons at our Guadalajara airport and for the border crossing at our Tijuana airport. In 2013, we spent
	Ps.686.3&nbsp;million on capital expenditures, principally for expansion and remodeling of terminal buildings and improvements to runways and aprons at the Guadalajara, Los Cabos, Tijuana, La Paz and Manzanillo airports.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Capital Expenditures in Jamaica
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Every
	five-year period, MBJA is entitled to submit to the JCAA its proposal for increases to the maximum regulated charges together with investment commitments (including capital expenditures for capital projects and required improvements at the Montego
	Bay airport under MBJA&#146;s concession agreement). Upon the JCAA&#146;s approval of the new maximum regulated charges, these commitments become binding obligations under the terms of MBJA&#146;s concession.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In November 2014, the JCAA approved new maximum regulated charges that assume capital investments (including scheduled maintenance) for the
	period from April 2015 to March 2020 estimated to cost approximately U.S.$38.0 million. It is our understanding that, under the terms of the concession agreement with the AAJ, these committed capital investments must be met over the 5-year period
	and not on an annual basis. In 2015, MBJA made investments of approximately U.S.$0.7 million in capital expenditures, which was fully dedicated to the replacement of equipment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Share Repurchase Program
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the
	aggregate, as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, we held 35,424,453 shares in our treasury worth approximately Ps.1.7&nbsp;billion, at an average price of Ps.48.93 per share; as of April&nbsp;10,&nbsp;2016, we held 35,424,453 shares at an average price
	of Ps.48.93 per share.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2013, a share repurchase program
	for Series&nbsp;B shares was approved for a maximum amount of Ps.640&nbsp;million for the twelve months following April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2013. During that period, we repurchased 5,145,053 shares at an average price of Ps.67.26 for
	Ps.346.1&nbsp;million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the General Ordinary Shareholder&#146;s Meeting held on April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014, a share repurchase program
	for Series&nbsp;B shares was approved for a maximum amount of Ps.400&nbsp;million for the twelve months following April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014. During that period, we did not repurchase any shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Critical Accounting Policies
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We prepare
	our audited consolidated financial statements in conformity with IFRS.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We base our estimates and judgments on our historical experience,
	on technical merits for tax positions, on financial projections and on various other reasonable factors that together form the basis for making judgments about the carrying values of our assets and liabilities. Our actual results may differ from
	these estimates under different assumptions or conditions. We evaluate our estimates and judgments on an ongoing basis. Our significant accounting policies are described in Note&nbsp;3 to our audited consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We believe our most critical accounting policies that result in the application of estimates and/or judgments are the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Contingencies and Provisions
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We
	are a party to a number of legal proceedings. Under IFRS, liabilities are recognized in the financial statements when a loss is both estimable and probable. If the loss is neither probable nor estimable or if the likelihood of a loss is remote, no
	amounts are recognized in the financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Allowance for Doubtful Accounts
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We systematically and periodically review the aging and collection of our accounts receivable and record an allowance for doubtful accounts
	when evidence exists that they will not be fully recoverable. We believe such risk is adequately covered by guarantee deposits in cash or other kind of guarantees by clients.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Income Taxes
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In conformity
	with IFRS, we recognize deferred tax assets and liabilities based on the differences between the financial statement carrying amounts and the tax basis of assets and liabilities. At year-end for 2013, 2014 and 2015, we recorded, within the deferred
	income tax asset, an estimated amount of recoverable asset tax paid of Ps.291.7&nbsp;million, Ps.233.1&nbsp;million and Ps.168.1&nbsp;million, respectively, based on financial projections that show that we will recover the excess of asset tax over
	income tax relating to our Guanajuato, Guadalajara, Puerto Vallarta and Tijuana airports. As a result of changes in Mexican tax law (see &#147;Item&nbsp;5,
<I>
	Operating and Financial Review and Prospects &#150; Overview &#150; Taxation
</I>
	&#148;),
	the asset tax balance may be recovered through rebates of up to 10% of the total asset tax paid out and pending recovery over the next ten years (starting in 2008), provided that this sum does not exceed the difference between the income tax paid
	during the period and the asset tax paid during the years 2007, 2006 and 2005, whichever is lower, whenever the income tax exceeds asset tax in any of those years. Additionally, we have recorded a tax loss carryforward, expiring in 2048 as permitted
	by the Mexican tax authorities for concession operation relating to our Aguascalientes and Morelia airports, and for ourselves, which has ten years to apply its tax loss. We regularly review our deferred tax assets for recoverability based on
	historical taxable income, projected future taxable income and related income tax expense compared to future estimated asset tax and the expected timing of the reversals of existing temporary differences. If these estimates and related assumptions
	change in the future, we may be required to make additional adjustments to our deferred tax assets, which may result in a reduction of, or an increase in, income tax expense. Based on our financial projections, up to December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, we
	will recognize deferred income taxes based on that expectation. In 2013, 2014 and 2015, we reduced the recoverable income taxes paid
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	141
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage148"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	on dividends for a total amount of Ps.0.5&nbsp;million, Ps.32.6&nbsp;million and Ps.11.4&nbsp;million, respectively, as we did not believe we would recover those amounts in future years. Every
	year we review the amount of income taxes paid on dividends according to our financial projections and determine the amount that could be recovered.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Impairment in the Value of Long-Lived Assets
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We must test for impairment when indicators of potential impairment in the carrying amount of tangible and intangible long-lived assets in use
	exist, unless there is conclusive evidence that the indicators of impairment are temporary. An impairment is recorded when the carrying amount of long-lived assets exceeds the greater of the present value of future net cash flows provided by the
	assets or the net sales price upon disposal. Present value of future net cash flows is based on management&#146;s projections of future operations, discounted using current interest rates. Our evaluations throughout the year and up to the date of
	this filing did not reveal any impairment of tangible and intangible long-lived assets. We can give no assurance that our evaluations will not change as a result of new information or developments which may change our future projections of net cash
	flows or the related discount rates and result in future impairment charges.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Accounting for the Concession
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	We believe we have carried out a comprehensive implementation of the standards applicable to the accounting treatment of our concession
	and have determined that, among others IFRIC&nbsp;12 is applicable to us. We treat our investments related to improvements and upgrades to be performed in connection with our Master Development Programs and Capital Development Program under the
	intangible asset model established by IFRIC&nbsp;12 and do not recognize a provision for maintenance, as all investments required by the Master Development Programs and Capital Development Program, regardless of their nature, directly increase the
	maximum tariff per traffic unit. Accordingly, all amounts invested under the Master Development Programs and Capital Development Program have a direct correlation to the amount of fees we will be able to charge each passenger or cargo service
	provider, and thus, a direct correlation to the amount of revenues we will be able to generate. As a result, we define all expenditures associated with investments required by the Master Development Programs and Capital Development Program as
	revenue generating activities given that they ultimately provide future benefits, whereby subsequent improvements and upgrades made to the concession are recognized as intangible assets based on the principles of IFRIC&nbsp;12. Additionally,
	compliance with the committed investments per the Master Development Programs and Capital Development Program is mandatory, as well as the fulfillment of the maximum tariff and therefore, in case of a failure to meet any one of these obligations
	(Master Development Program or Capital Development Program amounts or maximum tariff or maximum regulated charges), we could be subject to sanctions and our Mexican concessions or MBJA&#146;s concession could be revoked. See &#147;Item&nbsp;4,
<I>
	Information on the Company &#150; Regulatory Framework &#150; General Obligations of Concession Holders
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Depreciation and
	Amortization
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In light of the nature of our business and our concessions, we make certain assumptions and professional judgments
	regarding recognition of depreciation and amortization of our tangible and intangible assets. Depreciation of our tangible assets is calculated under the straight-line method based on the useful lives of the related assets. The estimated useful life
	and the depreciation method are reviewed at the end of each year, and the effect of any changes in the estimate recorded is recognized on a prospective basis. To determine the amortization period of intangible assets, we focus either on the period
	over which they will generate future economic benefits or the concession term, whichever is less. We believe that the decisions made are the most reasonable based on information available, on the judgments made and the way in which we manage our
	operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	142
</P>
