</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Fair Value of the DCA Acquisition Assets
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	Under IFRS&nbsp;3 &#150;
<I>
	Business Combinations
</I>
	, an acquirer of a business accounts for the acquisition of a control position
	using the &#147;acquisition method,&#148; which generally recognizes the assets acquired and liabilities assumed at their acquisition-date fair values.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As a result of the DCA acquisition, we completed our measurement of the acquisition-date fair values of the acquired assets and assumed
	liabilities. DCA&#146;s participation in SCL, however, was not recognized because the Santiago de Chile airport concession&#146;s term expired on September&nbsp;30, 2015; we expect to recover approximately Ps.85.0 million from SCL by 2017 through
	dividend and capital repayments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Using this &#147;acquisition method,&#148; we measured an acquisition-date fair value of
	Ps.3.97&nbsp;billion for the net assets held by DCA and MBJA, comprising a non-controlling interest of Ps.852.8&nbsp;million and a net asset value for our controlling interest of Ps.3.12&nbsp;billion. This acquisition-date fair value net asset
	amount, when compared to the total payment amount of Ps.2.93&nbsp;billion at the acquisition date, generates a bargain purchase gain in fair value of Ps.189.7&nbsp;million, which is recognized in our consolidated statement of Profit or Loss and
	Other Comprehensive Income under Other Income.
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_37"></A>

</P>

</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" ALIGN="CENTER">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our consolidated financial statements contemplate the effects of IFRS 9, IFRS 15 and IFRS 16. At the date of
	this report, we have not fully assessed the effects of adopting the other new standards and amendments on our consolidated financial information.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The following is a summary of these recently issued accounting standards.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	IFRS 14
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Regulatory Deferral Accounts
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IFRS&nbsp;14 specifies the accounting for deferral account balances arising from regulated activities. The standard is applicable to an entity
	that recognizes, in its first IFRS financial statements, regulatory deferral account balances in accordance with its previous accounting framework. The standard permits entities to continue to use, in its first and subsequent IFRS financial
	statements, the policies adopted under its previous accounting framework with respect to regulatory deferral account balances, with limited changes. In addition, the standard requires the separate presentation of regulatory deferral account balances
	in the statement of financial position and to present the movement of those accounts the statement of profit or loss and other comprehensive income. The standard also requires specific disclosures to identify the nature of, and risks associated
	with, the rate regulation that has resulted in the recognition of regulatory deferral account balances in accordance with this standard.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	143
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage150"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not anticipate that the application of IFRS&nbsp;14 will have a material impact on our
	consolidated financial statements
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	IFRS 15
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In May&nbsp;2014, IFRS&nbsp;15 was issued which establishes a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue
	arising from contracts with customers. IFRS&nbsp;15 will supersede the current revenue recognition guidance including IAS&nbsp;18
<I>
	&#150; Revenue
</I>
	, IAS 11
<I>
	&#150; Construction Contracts
</I>
	and the related interpretations when it becomes
	effective.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The core principle of IFRS&nbsp;15 is that an entity should recognize revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods
	or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services. Specifically, the standard introduces a 5-step approach to revenue recognition:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Step 1: Identify the contract(s) with a customer
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Step 2: Identify the performance obligations in the contract
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Step 3: Determine the transaction price
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Step 4: Allocate the transaction price to the performance obligations in the contract
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	Step 5: Recognize revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a performance obligation
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under
	IFRS&nbsp;15, an entity recognizes revenue when (or as) a performance obligation is satisfied, i.e. when &#145;control&#146; of the goods or services underlying the particular performance obligation is transferred to the customer. Far more
	prescriptive guidance has been added in IFRS&nbsp;15 to deal with specific scenarios. Furthermore, extensive disclosures are required by IFRS&nbsp;15.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We anticipate that the application of IFRS&nbsp;15 in the future may have a material impact on the amounts reported and disclosures made in
	our consolidated financial statements. However, it is not practicable to provide a reasonable estimate of the effect of IFRS&nbsp;15 until we perform a detailed review.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	Amendments to IFRS&nbsp;11
</I>
</B>
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Accounting for Acquisitions of Interests in Joint Operations
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IFRS&nbsp;11 provide guidance on how to account for the acquisition of a joint operation that constitutes a business as
	defined in IFRS&nbsp;3
<I>
	&#150; Business Combinations
</I>
	. Specifically, the amendments state that the relevant principles on accounting for business combinations in IFRS&nbsp;3 and other standards (e.g. IAS&nbsp;36 &#150;
<I>
	Impairment of
	Assets
</I>
	regarding impairment testing of a cash generating unit to which goodwill on acquisition of a joint operation has been allocated) should be applied. The same requirements should be applied to the formation of a joint operation if and only
	if an existing business is contributed to the joint operation by one of the parties that participate in the joint operation. A joint operator is also required to disclose the relevant information required by IFRS&nbsp;3 and other standards for
	business combinations. The amendments to IFRS&nbsp;11 apply prospectively for annual periods beginning on or after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not anticipate that the application of these amendments to IFRS&nbsp;11 will have a material impact our consolidated financial
	statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	144
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage151"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	Amendments to IAS 16 IAS 38
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Clarification of Acceptable Methods of Depreciation
	and Amortization
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IAS&nbsp;16 prohibit entities from using a revenue-based depreciation method for items of property,
	plant and equipment. The amendments to&nbsp;IAS 38 introduce a rebuttable presumption that revenue is not an appropriate basis for amortization of an intangible asset. This presumption can only be rebutted in the following two limited circumstances:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(a)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	when the intangible asset is expressed as a measure of revenue; or
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	(b)
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	when it can be demonstrated that revenue and consumption of the economic benefits of the intangible asset are highly correlated.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments apply prospectively for annual periods beginning on or after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Currently, we use the straight-line method for depreciation and amortization for property, plant and equipment, and intangible assets
	respectively. We believe that the straight-line method is the most appropriate method to reflect the consumption of economic benefits inherent in the respective assets and accordingly, we do not anticipate that the application of these amendments to
	IAS&nbsp;16 and IAS&nbsp;38 will have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	IFRS 9
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Financial
	Instruments
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IFRS 9, issued in November&nbsp;2009, introduced new requirements for the classification and measurement of financial
	assets. IFRS&nbsp;9 was subsequently amended in October&nbsp;2010 to include requirements for the classification and measurement of financial liabilities and for derecognition and in November&nbsp;2013 to include the new requirements for general
	hedge accounting. Another revised version of IFRS&nbsp;9 was issued in July&nbsp;2014 mainly to include (i)&nbsp;impairment requirements for financial assets and (ii)&nbsp;limited amendments to the classification and measurement requirements by
	introducing a &#145;fair value through other comprehensive income&#146; (FVTOCI) measurement category for certain simple debt instruments.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Key requirements of IFRS&nbsp;9 are:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	All recognized financial assets that are within the scope of IAS 39 &#150;
<I>
	Financial Instruments: Recognition and Measurement
</I>
	are required to be subsequently measured at amortized cost or fair value.
	Specifically, debt investments that are held within a business model whose objective is to collect the contractual cash flows, and that have contractual cash flows that are solely payments of principal and interest on the principal outstanding are
	generally measured at amortized cost at the end of subsequent accounting periods. Debt instruments that are held within a business model whose objective is achieved both by collecting contractual cash flows and selling financial assets, and that
	have contractual terms that give rise on specified dates to cash flows that are solely payments of principal and interest on the principal amount outstanding, are measured at FVTOCI. All other debt investments and equity investments are measured at
	their fair value at the end of subsequent accounting periods. In addition, under IFRS&nbsp;9, entities may make an irrevocable election to present subsequent changes in the fair value of an equity investment (that is not held for trading) in other
	comprehensive income, with only dividend income generally recognized in net income (loss).
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	With regard to the measurement of financial liabilities designated as of fair value through profit or loss,
	IFRS&nbsp;9 requires that the amount of change in the fair value of the financial liability that is attributable to changes in the credit risk of that liability is presented in other comprehensive income, unless the recognition of the effects of
	changes in the liability&#146;s credit
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	145
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage152"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE=" MARGIN-TOP:0PT ; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	risk in other comprehensive income would create or enlarge an accounting mismatch in profit or loss. Changes in fair value attributable to a financial liability&#146;s credit risk are not
	subsequently reclassified to profit or loss. Under IAS&nbsp;39, the entire amount of the change in the fair value of the financial liability designated as fair value through profit or loss is presented in profit or loss.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	In relation to the impairment of financial assets, IFRS&nbsp;9 requires an expected credit loss model, as opposed to an incurred credit loss model under IAS&nbsp;39. The expected credit loss model requires an entity to
	account for expected credit losses and changes in those expected credit losses at each reporting date to reflect changes in credit risk since initial recognition. In other words, it is no longer necessary for a credit event to have occurred before
	credit losses are recognized.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	The new general hedge accounting requirements retain the three types of hedge accounting mechanisms currently available in IAS&nbsp;39. Under IFRS&nbsp;9, greater flexibility has been introduced to the types of
	transactions eligible for hedge accounting, specifically broadening the types of instruments that qualify for hedging instruments and the types of risk components of non-financial items that are eligible for hedge accounting. In addition, the
	effectiveness test has been overhauled and replaced with the principle of an &#145;economic relationship&#146;. Retrospective assessment of hedge effectiveness is also no longer required. Enhanced disclosure requirements about an entity&#146;s risk
	management activities have also been introduced.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We anticipate that the application of IFRS&nbsp;9 in the future may have a
	material impact on amounts reported in respect of our financial assets and financial liabilities. However, it is not practicable to provide a reasonable estimate of the effect of IFRS&nbsp;9 until we undertake a detailed review.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	Amendments to IAS 16 and IAS 41
</I>
</B>
	&#150;
<B>
	Agriculture: Bearer Plants
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IAS 16 and IAS 41 define a bearer plant and require biological assets that meet the definition of a bearer plant to be
	accounted for as property, plant and equipment in accordance with IAS 16, instead of IAS 41. The produce growing on bearer plants continues to be accounted for in accordance with IAS 41.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not anticipate that the application of these amendments will have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	Amendments to IFRS 10, IFRS 12 and IAS 28
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Investment Entities: Applying the Consolidation Exception
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IFRS 10, IFRS 12 and IAS 28 clarify that the exemption from preparing consolidated financial statements is available to a
	parent company that is a subsidiary of an investment company, even if the investment company measures all its subsidiaries at fair value in accordance with IFRS 10. The amendments also clarify that the requirement for an investment company to
	consolidate a subsidiary providing services related to the former&#146;s investment activities applies only to subsidiaries that are not investment entities themselves.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not anticipate that the application of these amendments will have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	146
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage153"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Annual Improvements to IFRSs 2012-2014 Cycle
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The 2012-2014 Annual Improvements cycle for IFRS amendments include a number of amendments to various IFRSs, which are summarized below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IFRS 5 &#150;
<I>
	Non-current Assets Held for Sale and Discontinued Operations
</I>
	introduce specific guidance in IFRS 5 for
	when an Company reclassifies an asset (or disposal group) from held for sale to held for distribution to owners (or vice versa). The amendments clarify that such a change should be considered as a continuation of the original plan of disposal and
	hence requirements set out in IFRS 5 regarding the change of sale plan do not apply. The amendments also provide additional guidance to clarify when held-for-distribution accounting is discontinued.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The amendments to IFRS 7 &#150;
<I>
	Financial Instruments: Disclosures
</I>
	provide additional guidance to clarify whether a servicing contract
	is continuing involvement in a transferred asset for the purpose of the disclosures required in relation to transferred assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The
	amendments to IAS 19 &#150;
<I>
	Employee Benefits
</I>
	clarify that the rate used to discount post-employment benefit obligations should be determined by reference to market yields at the end of the reporting period on high-quality corporate bonds.
	The assessment of the depth of a market for high-quality corporate bonds should be at the currency level (i.e. the same currency as the benefits are to be paid). For currencies for which there is no deep market in such high quality corporate bonds,
	the market yields at the end of the reporting period on government bonds denominated in that currency should be used instead.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not
	anticipate that the application of these amendments will have a material impact on our consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
</B>
<B>
<I>
	IFRS 16
</I>
</B>
<B>
	&#150; Leases
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IFRS&nbsp;16 was issued in January 2016 and supersedes IAS&nbsp;17 &#150;
<I>
	Leases
</I>
	and related interpretations. The
	new standard brings most leases on-balance sheet for lessees under a single model, eliminating the distinction between operating and finance leases. Lessor accounting, however, remains largely unchanged and the distinction between operating and
	finance leases is retained. IFRS&nbsp;16 is effective for periods beginning on or after January1, 2019, with earlier adoption permitted if IFRS&nbsp;15 &#150;
<I>
	Revenue from Contracts with Customers
</I>
	has also been applied.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under IFRS&nbsp;16, a lessee recognizes a right-of-use asset and a lease liability. The right-of-use asset is treated similarly to other
	non-financial assets and depreciated accordingly and the liability accrues interest. This will typically produce a front-loaded expense profile (whereas operating leases under IAS&nbsp;17 would typically have had straight-line expenses) as an
	assumed linear depreciation of the right-of-use asset and the decreasing interest on the liability will lead to an overall decrease of expense over the reporting period.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The lease liability is initially measured at the present value of the lease payments payable over the lease term, discounted at the rate
	implicit in the lease if that can be readily determined. If that rate cannot be readily determined, the lessee shall use their incremental borrowing rate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	However, a lessee may elect to account for lease payments as an expense on a straight-line basis over the lease term for leases with a lease
	term of twelve months or less and containing no purchase options (this election is made by class of underlying asset); and leases where the underlying asset has a low value when new, such as personal computers or small items of office furniture
	(this election can be made on a lease-by-lease basis).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	147
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage154"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	IFRS 16 establishes different transitional provisions, including retrospective application or the
	modified retrospective application where the comparative period is not restated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We anticipate that the application of IFRS 16 in the
	future may have a material impact on the amounts reported and disclosures made in our consolidated financial statements. However, it is not practicable to provide a reasonable estimate of the effect of IFRS 16 until we perform a detailed review.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Off-balance Sheet Arrangements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We
	are not party to any off-balance sheet arrangements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Tabular Disclosure of Contractual Obligations
</B>
</P>

	The following table summarizes our contractual obligations as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

<EFX_DIRECTORS_AND_OFFICERS>
<A NAME="FIS_DIRECTORS_AND_OFFICERS"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_16">
</A>
	Item&nbsp;6.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Directors, Senior Management and Employees
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Directors
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The board of directors is responsible for the management of our business. Pursuant to our bylaws, our board of directors generally must consist
	of eleven members. Under Mexican law, at least 25 percent of our directors must be independent (as determined by our shareholders at each annual General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting, applying the provisions of our bylaws and relevant Mexican
	and other laws); under the Securities Market Law, the National Banking and Securities Commission may object to such designation of independence. Currently, our board of directors comprises eleven members.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our bylaws provide that the holders of Series&nbsp;BB shares are entitled to elect four members to the board of directors and their
	alternates. Our remaining directors are elected by the holders of our Series&nbsp;B shares (who do not elect alternates). Under our bylaws, each shareholder or group of shareholders owning
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	148
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage155"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	10% of our capital stock in the form of Series&nbsp;B shares is entitled to elect one member to the board of directors. Also our bylaws prevent any Series&nbsp;B shareholders, individually, or
	together with related parties, from appointing more than one board member, even if the shareholder owns more than 10% of our outstanding capital stock (because any shares in excess of the 10% maximum do not have any voting rights under our bylaws).
	The other directors to be elected by the holders of our Series&nbsp;B shares are elected by majority vote of all holders of Series&nbsp;B shares present at the shareholders&#146; meeting, except for those Series&nbsp;B shareholders that already
	participated in any 10% board member designation. Selection of independent directors is conducted through an executive search firm tasked with locating individuals with appropriate profiles. Directors are elected for one-year terms at the ordinary
	shareholders&#146; meeting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	At our April&nbsp;21,&nbsp;2015, General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting, several changes were
	approved to the composition of our board of directors, including the ratification of new members. The composition of our board of directors as of the date of this report is set forth in the following table, which lists the title, date of
	appointment, age and alternate, as applicable, of each of our current directors, however, this composition could change in the Ordinary Shareholders Meeting to be held on April&nbsp;26,&nbsp;2016. In the past, certain of our shareholders have
	challenged the composition of our board of directors. For more information see &#147;Item&nbsp;8,
<I>
	Financial Information &#150; Legal Proceedings &#150; Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. seeks to void certain resolutions adopted at our corporate
	shareholders&#146; meetings
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Laura D&iacute;ez Barroso Azc&aacute;rraga.
</B>
	Mrs.&nbsp;D&iacute;ez Barroso is chairwoman of our board of directors since 2015 and
	chairwoman of Fundaci&oacute;n GAP since its establishment in 2013. She is also a member of the board of directors of Telmex and Grupo Financiero Inbursa, as well as president and general director of the LCA Capital economic group. She has been a
	regular board member of Royal Caribbean International, ProMujer M&eacute;xico, Telmex Internacional and the Fundaci&oacute;n del Centro Hist&oacute;rico de la Ciudad de M&eacute;xico, A.C, as well as president of international publishers Editorial
	Eres and Editorial Televisa. Mrs.&nbsp;D&iacute;ez Barroso participates in philanthropic works in her role as chairwoman of Fundaci&oacute;n GAP and president of the board of trustees of the museum of San Ildefonso College in Mexico City.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Eduardo S&aacute;nchez Navarro Redo.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;S&aacute;nchez was chairman of our board of directors from April 2012 to April
	2015. He is currently chairman of the board of AMP. He is the founder of Grupo Questro, a real estate investment group with substantial holdings in Los Cabos, including luxury resorts and residential developments such as Cabo Real and Puerto Los
	Cabos. He is also a member of the board of directors and vice chairman of CULTIBA (the holding company for GEPP and Grupo Azucarero) and a member of the Mexican Resort Development Association (AMDETUR) since 1991, which is an organization that
	includes 90% of tourism real estate developers in the country. He is the vice president of the National Tourist Business Counsel (CNET) and has served as president of the Hotels and Tourism Companies Investors Association (AIHET). He is also
	president and founder of the Coordinating Counsel of Los Cabos.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	149
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Jos&eacute; Vicente Corta Fern&aacute;ndez.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Corta has been a member of our board
	of directors since April 2015. He has an in-depth knowledge of law and financial regulations, serving as a member of the board of directors of different entities within Mexico&#146;s financial services industry and speaking frequently on financial
	issues. Similarly, he has provided financial advisory services to the World Bank Group and the International Monetary Fund. Before joining the law firm of White&nbsp;&amp; Case LLP as a partner, he was chairman of the board of directors of
	Mexico&#146;s National Retirement Savings Commission (&#147;CONSAR&#148;) and executive secretary of Mexico&#146;s Bank Savings Protection Institute (&#147;IPAB&#148;). He is a member and ex-chairman of the Advisory Board of UNICEF in Mexico. In
	2006, the World Economic Forum named him a Young Global Leader. Mr.&nbsp;Corta was included on the list of the 300 most influential leaders in Mexico published by a specialized magazine Mr.&nbsp;Corta holds degrees in law from the Universidad
	Iberoamericana and the University of Warwick.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Francisco Javier Mar&iacute;n San Andr&eacute;s
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Mar&iacute;n was
	elected to the Company&#146;s board of directors on August&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2001 as a director nominee. He is CEO of Aena Aeropuertos, S.A. (&#147;Aena&#148;). He also serves as managing director of Aena Desarrollo Internacional, a subsidiary that
	manages Aena&#146;s operations outside of Spain, a member of the board of directors of the engineering company Ingenier&iacute;a y Econom&iacute;a del Transporte S.A. (INECO), and a member of the board of AMP. He joined Aena in 1991 and he has
	occupied different executive posts since then, including CEO of Air Navigation, Director of Corporate Development, and CEO of Aena Internacional. He has also served in various positions at the Technical University of Madrid, in the Directorate
	General of Civil Aviation, in the Eurocontrol Experimental Centre in Paris, and in the business group Indra Sistemas S.A. Mr.&nbsp;Mar&iacute;n has a degree in aeronautical engineering from the Universidad Polit&eacute;cnica of Madrid and a
	Master&#146;s Degree in Financial Management from the Official Chamber of Commerce and Industry of Madrid, and he has completed an Executive Management Program (PADE) at the IESE Business School.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Eduardo Gall&aacute;stegui Armella
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Gall&aacute;stegui has been a member of our board of directors since he was
	appointed by Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. in July&nbsp;2010. Mr.&nbsp;Gall&aacute;stegui has a wide range of professional experience advising Mexican and foreign companies on matters of corporate governance, commercial and financial law,
	mergers and acquisitions, arbitration, telecommunications, antitrust, pharmaceuticals and foreign investments in Mexico. Since February 2015, he has been the Managing Partner of law firm DLA Piper Mexico, S.C. Before joining DLA Piper, he was a
	founding partner of law firm Gall&aacute;stegui y Lozano, S.C., which merged with DLA Piper. Prior to founding his own law firm, he was previously a partner at Vazquez Pando, Celis Azuela y Asociados from 1982 to 1985. Previously, he was an attorney
	with Noriega y Escobedo, S.C. and Gillette de M&eacute;xico, S.A. de C.V. Mr.&nbsp;Gall&aacute;stegui holds a degree in law from the Universidad Iberoamericana.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Carlos C&aacute;rdenas Guzm&aacute;n.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;C&aacute;rdenas has been a member of our board of directors since 2011, where he also
	serves as president of our Audit Committee. After 39 years of active service as an accountant, he retired as a partner from Ernst&nbsp;&amp; Young Mexico. He also currently serves on the boards of directors and audit committees of numerous large
	Mexican companies, including as secretary and former president of The American British Cowdray Medical Center, I.A.P., board member and president of the Audit Committee of CHG-MERIDIAN M&eacute;xico, S.A.P.I. de C.V., board member of Reaseguradora
	Patria, S.A.B.; and Statutory Auditor of General de Seguros, S.A.B. He is also a member of several business and professional associations; most notably, he served as President of the Mexican Institute of Certified Public Accountants (IMCP) for 2012
	to 2013. Mr.&nbsp;C&aacute;rdenas is a Certified Public Accountant, with a degree from the Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Guadalajara and a Master&#146;s Degree in Tax Law from the Universidad Panamericana (IPADE).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	150

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Joaquin Vargas Guajardo.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Vargas was elected as an independent director to the
	Company&#146;s board of directors on April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2012. He is chairman of the board of directors of Grupo MVS Comunicaciones, S.A. de C.V., which includes, among others, radio stations such as MVS News, EXA FM and La Mejor, as well as DISH
	satellite television services and the television channel 52MX. He serves on the boards of directors of publically traded companies Vitro, Grupo Financiero Santander and M&eacute;dica Sur. He is also a member of the boards of directors of El
	Universal newspaper, Costamex, the Panamericana University and of the Patronage of the National Nutrition Institute, among others.
<B>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	&Aacute;lvaro Fern&aacute;ndez Garza.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Fern&aacute;ndez was elected to the Company&#146;s board of directors on
	February&nbsp;26,&nbsp;2014 as a provisional director nominee and serves as an independent director. He serves on the boards of Vitro, ALFA and CYDSA, as well as of the Universidad de Monterrey (UDEM) and the Museo de Arte Contempor&aacute;neo de
	Monterrey (MARCO). Mr.&nbsp;Fern&aacute;ndez holds a Bachelor&#146;s Degree in Economics from the University of Notre Dame and MBAs from the Instituto Tecnol&oacute;gico de Estudios Superiores de Monterrey (ITESM) and from Georgetown University.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Juan Diez-Canedo Ru&iacute;z
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Diez-Canedo was elected as an independent director to the Company&#146;s board of
	directors on April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014. After over a decade in banking, during which he led Banco Internacional (currently HSBC) through some of the major privatizations at the time, including Telmex, Mexicana de Aviaci&oacute;n, Industrias Conasupo
	and Fertimex, he was appointed CEO of CINTRA, the holding company for the Mexican airlines Aerom&eacute;xico Group and Mexicana, in November 1999. From 2002 to 2008, he was president of FODECO, a consulting firm. Since 2009, he serves as the
	president of Financiera Local. He has been an independent member of the boards of directors of Banco Mercantil del Norte (Banorte), Gruma, Gimsa, Telmex, Alcatel, Fondo de Cultura Econ&oacute;mica and Deportes Mart&iacute;. At Banorte, he is also a
	member of the Consejo Regional Metropolitano. From 1995 until November 2013, he was an independent member and president of the audit committees of the boards of directors of GRUMA, S.A.B. de C.V. (a NYSE-listed company) and of its subsidiary Grupo
	Industrial Maseca, S.A.B. de C.V. Mr.&nbsp;Diez-Canedo holds a Bachelor&#146;s Degree in Economics from Instituto Tecnol&oacute;gico Aut&oacute;nomo de Mexico (ITAM) and a Ph.D. in Economics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	&Aacute;ngel Losada Moreno
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Losada was elected as an independent director to the Company&#146;s board of directors on
	April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014. He is currently chairman of the board of directors and CEO of Grupo Gigante, S.A.B. de C.V. He is a member of the boards of directors of Tel&eacute;fonos de M&eacute;xico, S.A. de C.V., Grupo Financiero Banamex, the
	Federico G&oacute;mez Children&#146;s Hospital, Laboratorios Novag and MD Anderson. He has also served as chairman of the board of directors of the Mexican National Association of Retailers (Asociaci&oacute;n Nacional de Tiendas de Autoservicio y
	Departamentales, A.C., or ANTAD), as a director and member of the board of directors of the Food Marketing Institute of the United States and as member of the board of Mexico City&#146;s National Chamber of Commerce. Mr.&nbsp;Losada holds a degree
	in business administration from Universidad An&aacute;huac.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Roberto Servitje Achutegui.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Servitje was elected as an
	independent director to the Company&#146;s board of directors on April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2012. He has 25 years of experience in the food and beverage industry. He served as executive vice president and director of Grupo Bimbo, S.A., and as president of
	Grupo Altex S.A., a diversified agro-industrial group, since January&nbsp;2000. He is also a member of the boards of directors of various companies, such as Grupo Elektra, Banco Azteca, Grupo Lacrem (in Barcelona, Spain) and Financiera
	Independencia. He also serves as co-chairman of Mexico&#146;s &#147;Vision for Sustainable Agriculture&#148; at the World Economic Forum and as Treasurer of the Patronato de Arte Contempor&aacute;neo and of the Fundaci&oacute;n Olga y Rufino Tamayo.
	Mr.&nbsp;Servitje received a degree in business administration from Universidad Iberoamericana and an MBA in marketing and finance from Northwestern University (Kellogg).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Fernando Bosque Moh&iacute;no.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Bosque was named our CEO effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2011.
	He has over 35 years of experience in the airport sector. He began his career in 1976 the Federal Aviation and Transportation Department in Spain. Recently, he served as the CEO of MBJ Airports Limited, in Montego Bay, Jamaica, appointed by Abertis.
	He has extensive knowledge of the airport industry having previously been the Chief Financial Officer of AENA Internacional, one of our strategic partners. He served as a member of ASUR&#146;s Board, working as Ferrovial&#146;s concession director,
	and consequently has a strong understanding of the privatization structure of Mexican Airports. Mr.&nbsp;Bosque is a graduate in economics and business from the Universidad Aut&oacute;noma de Madrid.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Sa&uacute;l Villarreal Garc&iacute;a
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Villarreal was named our CFO effective on February&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2015. He joined
	the Company in October 2003 and has been responsible for overseeing Corporate Administration since that time; as a result, he has vast experience and knowledge of the Company, mainly from an Administrative and Financial Management aspect. In 2006,
	he participated in the Initial Public Offering process and more recently participated in the issuance of debt securities on the local market. Mr.&nbsp;Villarreal is a public accountant with an MBA from the University of Guadalajara and a
	master&#146;s degree in finance with a concentration in international accounting from the Universidad Panamericana.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Sergio
	Enrique Flores Ochoa
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Flores was named our General Counsel in February&nbsp;2002. Previously, he was the manager of legal matters for the ASA and an Assistant District Attorney for Mexico City. In addition, he was head of the
	legal department of INFONAVIT and legal manager for NAFIN. Mr.&nbsp;Flores received a degree in law, as well as a master&#146;s degree in law, from the Universidad Nacional Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico (UNAM).
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Jorge Luis Valdespino Rivera
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Valdespino was named our Director of Human Resources in August&nbsp;2006. He has fourteen
	years of experience as a human resources executive. He worked in the pharmaceutical industry at Searle de M&eacute;xico, S.A. de C.V. as Human Resources Manager, and in the automotive industry at Valeo Group as Human Resources Director, and at Hella
	de M&eacute;xico, S.A. de C.V. as Human Resources Corporate Director. Mr.&nbsp;Valdespino received an undergraduate degree in business administration and a postgraduate degree in human resources from the Universidad Tecnol&oacute;gica de
	M&eacute;xico.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Tomas Enrique Ram&iacute;rez Vargas.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Ram&iacute;rez was named our Director of Commercial Activities
	in August&nbsp;2013. He joined the Company in 2007 as the Commercial Development Manager and has previous experience in route development and infrastructure concessions. Mr.&nbsp;Ram&iacute;rez holds a bachelor&#146;s degree in management and
	finance from the Universidad Panamericana and an MBA through a joint program of the Instituto Tecnol&oacute;gico de Estudios Superiores de Monterrey (ITESM) and the Thunderbird School of Global Management.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">

</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Jos&eacute; Ignacio Ascac&iacute;bar Mart&iacute;nez
</B>
<B>
	.
</B>
	Mr.&nbsp;Ascac&iacute;bar was
	named our Director of Technical Operations in April&nbsp;2010. In 1989, he began his career at Iberia, L&iacute;neas A&eacute;reas de Espa&ntilde;a, S.A., where he was Manager of Flight Programs. In 1995, he became the Director of Information
	Systems at Aeropuertos Espa&ntilde;oles de AENA, in addition to being a member of Aeropuertos Espa&ntilde;oles&#146; Executive Committee. Mr.&nbsp;Ascac&iacute;bar holds a degree in Aeronautical Engineering from the Universidad Polit&eacute;cnica de
	Madrid, as well as an MBA from the Instituto de Empresa in Madrid, a Certificate in Business Development from IESE in Madrid, a master&#146;s degree in airport operations from ETSIA Polytechnic University in Madrid and a Certificate in European
	Studies from C.I.F.E. in Madrid.
<B>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The business address of our directors and executive officers is our principal executive
	headquarters.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Compensation of Directors and Executives
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	For 2015, the aggregate compensation paid to our seven independent directors was approximately Ps.5.2&nbsp;million. The compensation paid to
	the director appointed by Grupo M&eacute;xico was approximately of Ps.0.7&nbsp;million. We have not established any pension, retirement or similar benefits or arrangements for these individuals. These directors receive a base annual compensation of
	approximately U.S.$44,100 for their service on our board of directors. Additionally, for their services to our corporate governance committees, certain directors receive supplemental compensation: the president of our Audit Committee receives an
	additional 17.5% of the base annual compensation; members of our Audit Committee receive 10% of the base annual compensation; and members of our Acquisition Committee and our Compensation Committee receive 5% of the base annual compensation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under the technical assistance agreement with AMP, the four directors and four alternates elected by AMP do not receive compensation from us
	for serving on our board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The compensation paid to our six executive officers amounted to Ps.28.0&nbsp;million in 2015,
	including salaries (70%), bonuses (29%)&nbsp;and other compensation (1%). We have not established any pension, retirement or similar benefits or arrangements for these individuals through 2015. However, in 2016 we established a new long-term
	incentives plan for our executives, which seeks to encourage the retention and development of key management within the Company. The executive officers&#146; rights to exercise this compensation plan will vest at the end of 2019, subject to certain
	performance and profitability targets for the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	None of our directors, alternate directors or executive officers is the
	beneficial owner of more than 1% of any class of our capital stock, except as described in &#147;Item&nbsp;7,
<I>
	Major Shareholders and Related Party Transactions &#150; Major Shareholders
</I>
	.&#148; None of our directors or executive officers is
	entitled to benefits upon termination under their service contracts with us, except for what is due to them according to the Mexican Federal Labor Law. Additionally, we have not made personal loans to our directors or executive officers and do not
	have a stock option plan or any equivalent plan.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Board Committees
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our bylaws provide for four committees to assist the board of directors with the management of our business: an Operating Committee, an Audit
	and Corporate Practices Committee, an Acquisitions Committee and a Nominations and Compensation Committee. The Audit Committee, to which our bylaws have granted the duties provided for in the Securities Market Law for Mexican corporate practices
	committees, is the only legally required committee. The other committees have been established to assist the board of directors. The board of directors may establish further committees from time to time.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	153
</P>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Operating Committee
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Operating Committee, which, pursuant to our bylaws, shall have six members and three alternates, is responsible for, among other matters,
	proposing and approving certain plans and policies relating to our business, investments and administration, including approval of the Master Development Programs of our subsidiary concession holders, our dividend policy and investments of less than
	U.S.$3.0&nbsp;million that are not provided for in our annual budget. Pursuant to our bylaws, the board of directors is authorized to appoint the six members of the Operating Committee. Board members elected by the holders of Series&nbsp;BB shares
	have the right to appoint three of the committee members. As of the date of this report, the members of the Operating Committee are Fernando Bosque Moh&iacute;no, CEO, who chairs the committee; Carlos Rohm; Alejandro Cortina Gallardo; Tom&aacute;s
	Enrique Ram&iacute;rez Vargas, Director of Commercial Activities; Jos&eacute; Ignacio Ascac&iacute;bar Mart&iacute;nez, Director of Technical Operations; and Sa&uacute;l Villarreal Garc&iacute;a, Chief Financial Officer. Carlos Manuel Porr&oacute;n
	Suarez, Santiago Riveroll and Carlos Laviada Ocejo serve as alternates for Fernando Bosque Moh&iacute;no, Carlos Rohm and Alejandro Cortina Gallardo, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Audit and Corporate Practices Committee
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Audit and Corporate Practices Committee, which must have a minimum of three members, the majority of whom must be members of our board of
	directors, is responsible, among other things, for: (i)&nbsp;monitoring the compliance of our directors, officers and employees (and those of our subsidiaries) with our (and their) bylaws (
<I>
	estatutos sociales
</I>
	) and applicable law,
	(ii)&nbsp;naming, and supervising the work of, our independent auditors and (iii)&nbsp;receiving and investigating internal complaints or other information concerning our systems of internal control and other such matters. The Audit and Corporate
	Practices Committee is also responsible for reviewing our corporate governance and all related-party transactions (according to the requirements of our bylaws and the Mexican Market Law), including transactions with AMP. The members of the board of
	directors elected by the holders of Series&nbsp;BB shares are entitled to propose the appointment to the Audit and Corporate Practices Committee of the number of members representing 20% of the committee&#146;s total members, but at least one member
	who must also fulfill applicable independence requirements. The president of this committee is elected at the annual shareholders&#146; meeting. The composition of the Audit and Corporate Practices Committee must at all times be compliant with all
	applicable laws and regulations, including independence requirements, for every jurisdiction in which our securities are listed or quoted. As of the date of this report, the members of the Audit and Corporate Practices Committee are Carlos
	C&aacute;rdenas Guzm&aacute;n, Juan Diez-Canedo Ru&iacute;z and &Aacute;ngel Losada Moreno.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Acquisitions Committee
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Acquisitions Committee is responsible for ensuring compliance with our procurement policies set forth in our bylaws. Among other things,
	these policies require that the Acquisitions Committee approve any transaction or series of related transactions between us and a third party involving consideration in excess of U.S.$400,000 and that any contract between us, on the one hand, and
	AMP or any of its related parties, on the other hand, be awarded pursuant to a bidding process, which, in the case of AMP, must involve at least three other bidders. In the case of a proposed transaction between us and AMP or any related party, we
	are required to invite, pursuant to the bylaws, at least three contractors to bid on the transaction and, in the case that a third-party contractor&#146;s bid is equal to or less than AMP&#146;s bid, the transaction is awarded to the third-party
	contractor.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our bylaws provide that a shareholders&#146; meeting will determine the number of members of the Acquisitions Committee,
	which must be composed primarily of members of the board of directors. The members of the board of directors elected by the holders of Series&nbsp;BB shares are entitled to appoint to the committee the number of members representing 20% of its total
	members but at a minimum, one member. As of the date of this report, the Acquisitions Committee consists of proprietary members Rodrigo Marabini Ru&iacute;z and Joaquin Vargas Guajardo. Eduardo S&aacute;nchez Navarro Redo was elected to serve as an
	alternate member to Rodrigo Marabini Ru&iacute;z. A secretary has also been appointed who is not a member of the committee.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	154
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage161"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Nominations and Compensation Committee
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Nominations and Compensation Committee is responsible for nominating candidates for election to our board of directors and making
	recommendations regarding the compensation of our directors and officers. The committee also serves in a corporate governance role within the scope of its subject matter. Our bylaws provide that a shareholders&#146; meeting will determine the number
	of members of the committee. The holders of the Series&nbsp;B and Series&nbsp;BB shares, each acting as a class, are each entitled to name one member of the Nominations and Compensation Committee. The remaining members of the committee, if any, are
	designated by the two members who were selected by the Series&nbsp;B and Series&nbsp;BB shareholders. If these two members are unable to reach agreement, the remaining members of the committee will be designated by the majority of the votes in the
	shareholders&#146; meeting, provided that, in such case, holders of the Series&nbsp;BB Shares will be entitled to appoint 20% of the members but at a minimum, one member. Members of the committee serve for a term of one year. At each annual
	shareholders&#146; meeting, the Nominations and Compensation Committee is required to present a list of candidates for election as directors for the vote of the Series&nbsp;B shareholders. As of the date of this report, the members of the
	Nominations and Compensation Committee are Laura D&iacute;ez Barroso Azc&aacute;rraga and &Aacute;lvaro Fern&aacute;ndez Garza. Eduardo S&aacute;nchez Navarro Redo was elected to serve as an alternate member to Laura D&iacute;ez Barroso
	Azc&aacute;rraga.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<A NAME="eolPage162"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, 51.3% of our employees were non-unionized employees.
	The remaining 48.7% employees were unionized. All of our unionized employees are members of local chapters of the Mexican National Union of Airport Workers (
<I>
	Sindicato Nacional de Trabajadores de la Industria Aeroportuaria y Servicios Similares y
	Conexos de la Rep&uacute;blica Mexicana
</I>
	), an organization formed in 1998 whose members include employees of ASA as well as of the three other airport groups (the Southeast Group, the Mexico City Group and the Central-North Group) operating in
	Mexico. Labor relations with our employees are governed by one collective bargaining agreement relating to each one of our twelve airport subsidiaries; which is negotiated by the respective local chapter of the union. As is typical in Mexico, wages
	are renegotiated every year, while other terms and conditions of employment are renegotiated every two years. In 2014, we successfully renegotiated our collective bargaining agreement, thereby securing a favorable and productive work environment for
	our employees for 2015 and 2016. We believe that our relations with our employees are good, and the wages we pay our employees are similar to those paid to employees of similar airport operating companies in Mexico. During October&nbsp;2016, we will
	be required to renegotiate the collective bargaining agreement.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We offer a savings plan available to all of our Mexican employees
	pursuant to which our employees may make bi-weekly contributions of up to 13% of their pre-tax salaries. We make bi-weekly contributions matching each employee&#146;s contribution. Employees are entitled to withdraw funds from their accounts on an
	annual basis. In 2013, 2014 and 2015, we made a total of Ps.16.0&nbsp;million, Ps.15.1&nbsp;million and Ps.17.0&nbsp;million, respectively, in payments to employees&#146; accounts pursuant to the savings plan.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Funds in the savings plan may be used to make loans to employees and are otherwise invested in securities listed on the Mexican Stock Exchange
	or in treasury bills issued by the Mexican Treasury Department.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Employees in Jamaica
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	indicated:
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, 25.6% of MBJA&#146;s employees, comprising management and contract staff, were non-unionized employees and
	the remaining 74.4% employees were unionized. The unionized employees are members of two local trade unions: the Trade Union Congress (&#147;TUC&#148;) and Union of Technical, Administrative, and Supervisory Personnel (&#147;UTASP&#148;).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The current collective bargaining agreement with the TUC expired on February&nbsp;28, 2016. Fifty-four employees from MBJA&#146;s maintenance,
	engineering and emergency response service teams are
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	156

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	members of the TUC. The collective bargaining agreement historically covers wages and benefits and terms and conditions of employment for a two-year period. MBJA has received this union&#146;s
	requests, and it expects to commence renegotiations of the collective bargaining agreement with the TUC during the second quarter of 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The current collective bargaining agreement with the UTASP expired on March&nbsp;31, 2016. Seventy-one employees from MBJA&#146;s supervisory
	and administrative personnel across different departments are members of the UTASP. The collective bargaining agreement historically determines wages and benefits and terms and conditions of employment for a two-year period. MBJA has not yet
	received this union&#146;s requests, however, it expects to commence renegotiations of the collective bargaining agreement with the UTASP during the second quarter of 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2014, MBJA amicably renegotiated its collective bargaining agreements for both unions, thereby securing a continued favorable and
	productive work environment for its employees for 2014 through 2016. We anticipate amicable negotiations as MBJA continues to maintain a good relationship with both unions. Further, to our knowledge, MBJA pays comparable salaries and benefits to
	other similar enterprises in Jamaica.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	MBJA also facilitates voluntary employee salary deductions for personal savings.
</P>

	AMP holds all of our Series&nbsp;BB shares, representing 15% of our total share capital. Special rights and restrictions attached to our
	Series&nbsp;BB shares are described under &#147;Item&nbsp;4,

	Shareholders&#146; Meetings

	.&#148; As of April&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2016, approximately 17.9% of our Series&nbsp;B shares were held in the form of ADSs, and 65% of the holders of our ADSs (76 holders, including The Depository Trust Company) had
	registered addresses in the United States.
