<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	AMP Trust, Bylaws and Shareholders&#146; Agreement
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The rules governing the sale of our Series&nbsp;BB shares to AMP required that AMP place all of its Series&nbsp;BB shares in trust in order to
	guarantee AMP&#146;s performance of its obligations under the technical assistance agreement and AMP&#146;s commitment to maintain its interest in us for a specified period. Accordingly, AMP has placed its shares in trust with Bancomext. This trust
	provides that AMP may instruct Bancomext with respect to the voting of the shares held in trust that represent up to 10% of our capital stock; the remaining 5% is required to be voted in the same manner as the majority of all shares voted at the
	relevant shareholders&#146; meeting. Under our bylaws and the trust, AMP could not sell any of its Series&nbsp;BB shares before August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2004. Since the end of this no-sale period, AMP has been permitted to transfer up to 49% of its
	Series&nbsp;BB shares without restriction. After August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2009, AMP may sell in any year up to 20% of its remaining 51% ownership interest in us represented by Series&nbsp;BB shares. The terms of the trust will be extended for an
	additional fifteen years if, at the end of the initial fifteen-year term, AMP holds shares representing more than 10% of our capital stock. AMP may terminate the trust before the second fifteen-year term begins if (i)&nbsp;AMP holds less than 10% of
	our capital stock at the end of the initial term, and (ii)&nbsp;the technical services agreement has been terminated. AMP is required to deposit in the trust any additional shares of our capital stock that it acquires.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	AMP&#146;s shareholders have entered into a shareholders&#146; agreement that provides that AENA will have the right to appoint our
	director of technical operations, meanwhile (i)&nbsp;the appointment of AMP&#146;s representatives to our board of directors and board committees shall be made on a rotating basis, and (ii)&nbsp;any right of AMP regarding the appointment of our
	chief executive officer, chief financial officer, director of investor relations, general counsel, director of human resources, director of commercial activities, the secretary of our board of directors and most other matters relating to AMP&#146;s
	participation in us, must be made, in principle, pursuant to the unanimous consent of AMP&#146;s shareholders. When unanimous consent is not obtained, other mechanisms exist to avoid the resulting deadlocks. However, such deadlocks might still
	occur, which may affect our operations. See &#147;Item 3,
<I>
	Risk Factors &#150; Risks Related to our Controlling Shareholder &#150; AMP controls our management, and AMP&#146;s interests may differ from those of other shareholders. In the past,
	disputed among AMP&#146;s shareholders have affected us.
</I>
	&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under the terms of the participation agreement and the trust
	agreement, AMP&#146;s designated &#147;Mexican&#148; and &#147;operating&#148; partners were required to maintain their current 25.5% ownership interest in AMP until August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2014. On November&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2014, CMA and DCA entered into
	a stock purchase agreement and formalized the transaction through which CMA purchased from DCA 792,800,000 shares, representative of 33.33% of the capital stock of AMP. Although CMA became 66.66% owner of the capital stock of AMP as a result of this
	transaction, CMA and AENA have agreed that AENA&#146;s consent is required with respect to certain significant actions or decisions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_19">
</A>
	RELATED PARTY TRANSACTIONS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Arrangements with AMP and its Affiliates
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The rules for the sale of the Series&nbsp;BB shares required AMP, us and the SCT to enter into a participation agreement, which established the
	framework for the technical assistance agreement and the Banco Nacional de Comercio Exterior, S.N.C., or Bancomext, trust agreement.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Pursuant to the technical assistance agreement and the participation agreement, AMP and its shareholders agreed to provide management and
	consulting services and transfer to us technical assistance and technical and industry expertise related to the operation of airports. The agreement has an initial term of approximately fifteen years, but automatically renews for successive
	five-year terms unless one party provides the other a notice of termination at least 60 days prior to a scheduled expiration date. Despite the automatic renewal under Clause&nbsp;5.2 of the agreement, at our April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014, board of
	directors meeting, we requested the opinion of the board&#146;s independent directors with respect to the continuation of the agreement. The majority of our independent directors voted in favor of the five-year automatic renewal option. The
	agreement was thus automatically renewed on August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2014, for an additional five-year term.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	158
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage165"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A decision by us to renew or cancel the technical assistance agreement is subject to the approval
	of 51% of Series&nbsp;B shareholders other than AMP or any related party of AMP (to the extent that AMP or any such related party holds Series&nbsp;B shares). The agreement will only remain in effect if AMP continues to hold at least 7.65% of our
	capital stock. If the agreement does not remain in place, our management could change and due to the lack of technical assistance, our operations could be adversely and significantly affected.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Subsequent to January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2002, the technical assistance fee has been required to equal the greater of U.S.$4.0&nbsp;million adjusted
	annually for inflation (measured by the U.S. CPI) or 5% of our annual consolidated income from operations (calculated prior to deducting the technical assistance fee and depreciation and amortization in accordance with MFRS). We believe that this
	structure creates an incentive for AMP to increase our annual consolidated earnings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	The technical assistance agreement allows
	AMP, its shareholders and their affiliates to render additional services to us only if our Acquisitions Committee determines that these related parties have submitted the most favorable bid in a bidding process with at least three unrelated parties.
	This process is described in &#147;Item&nbsp;6,
<I>
	Directors, Senior Management and Employees &#150; Board Committees
</I>
	.&#148;
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In 2013, we recognized expenses of Ps.1.5 million (U.S.$114.2 thousand) that were paid to AMP. In 2014, we did not recognize any such
	expenses. In 2015, we recognized expenses of Ps.2.3 million (U.S.$133.0 thousand) that were paid to AMP. Pursuant to the technical assistance agreement, the fee paid to AMP and its affiliates was approximately Ps.171.5&nbsp;million
	(U.S.$13.1&nbsp;million), Ps.194.2&nbsp;million (U.S.$13.2&nbsp;million) and Ps.234.9&nbsp;million (U.S.$13.6&nbsp;million) for 2013, 2014 and 2015, respectively.
</P>

<EFX_LEGAL_PROCEEDINGS>
<A NAME="FIS_LEGAL_PROCEEDINGS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_21">
</A>
	LEGAL PROCEEDINGS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	General
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We are periodically involved in
	certain legal proceedings that are incidental to the normal conduct of our business, none of which is expected to have a material or adverse effect on our business. In addition to those legal proceedings in the ordinary course of our businesses, in
	recent years, we have also been subject, directly and indirectly, to the litigation proceedings that are summarized below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Litigation related to
	Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. and suits seeking to void certain of our bylaws
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Articles X and XII of our bylaws, among
	others, limit the ability of Series&nbsp;B shareholders, directly or with related parties, other than AMP, to hold more than 10% of our outstanding capital stock, and any shares held in excess of that amount must be sold in a public offering. In
	accordance with our bylaws, until the public offering of such shares takes place, such excess shares have no voting power and cannot be represented in any shareholders&#146; meeting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On June&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2011, Grupo M&eacute;xico announced that it intended to acquire more than 30% and up to 100% of our shares outstanding
	at that time, excluding treasury shares. Grupo M&eacute;xico and certain of its subsidiaries commenced legal proceedings, among others, seeking (i)&nbsp;to modify our bylaws to eliminate the foregoing limitations and (ii)&nbsp;to terminate
	AMP&#146;s special rights that stem from AMP&#146;s ownership of our Series&nbsp;BB shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	159
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage166"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In October&nbsp;2010, a legal proceeding was filed against us in a civil court in Mexico City.
	The complaint sought to have the court grant relief by, among others, declaring Articles X and XII of our bylaws void. The plaintiffs are Grupo M&eacute;xico and its subsidiary ITM. On September&nbsp;30,&nbsp;2011, the court issued a favorable
	decision for the plaintiffs, and we appealed this decision. On February&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2013, we were notified that an intermediate appellate court had confirmed the lower court&#146;s decision holding certain of our bylaws to be invalid. We filed a
	direct
<I>
	amparo
</I>
	appeal on March&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2013. On April&nbsp;10,&nbsp;2013, we were informed that the court ordered the suspension of the civil courts&#146; decisions, pending the resolution of our appeal. On February&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2014,
	the Mexican Supreme Court agreed to review the legal proceeding regarding ownership limits contained in our bylaws that impose a 10% ownership threshold, stating that it considered this issue a matter of national interest and significance, and
	referred the proceeding to the second chamber of the Supreme Court. On June&nbsp;17, 2015, the Mexican Supreme Court issued an
<I>
	amparo
</I>
	ruling upholding the validity of Articles X and XII of our bylaws regarding the limitations on ownership of
	our capital stock under Article 48, Section III of the Mexican Securities Law and remanded the case to the intermediate appellate court. Consequently, the challenges initiated by Grupo M&eacute;xico and ITM against these articles have been
	definitively concluded. In accordance with the decision of the Mexican Supreme Court, the Superior Court of Mexico City: i) declared that Grupo M&eacute;xico and ITM are in violation of our bylaws, resulting from the fact that together they hold
	more than the 10% of our capital stock; ii) ordered the sale by GM and ITM of the Series &#147;B&#148; shares held in excess of 10% of our capital stock; and iii) instructed that the sale should be conducted through a public offer (
<I>
	Oferta
	P&uacute;blica de Venta
</I>
	) in accordance with the laws of Mexico and Article XII of our bylaws. See &#147;Item&nbsp;3,
<I>
	Risk Factors &#150; Risks Related to Our Controlling Shareholder &#150; Certain actions by Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de
	C.V. may affect our management, financial condition or results of operations
</I>
	.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. seeks to void certain
	resolutions adopted at our corporate shareholders&#146; meetings
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting of April&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2011
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Prior to our General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on April&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2011, Grupo M&eacute;xico indicated its intent to
	appoint two members to our board of directors, one for each 10% ownership interest it held in us at the time. However, according to our bylaws, ownership of our common stock is limited to 10%, and consequently, the right of representation on our
	board of directors and the right to vote at our shareholders&#146; meetings is also limited to 10%. During the April&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2011, annual General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting, Grupo M&eacute;xico&#146;s request was rejected, and Grupo
	M&eacute;xico was asked to appoint a single board member in accordance with their rights under our bylaws. In response, Grupo M&eacute;xico initiated legal action seeking to nullify the resolutions adopted regarding the designation of
	representatives of our Series&nbsp;B shares to our board directors. On May&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2011, a civil court provisionally suspended the related resolutions. We appealed the decision on June&nbsp;17,&nbsp;2011, and after an intermediate appellate
	court confirmed the lower court&#146;s decision, we filed a direct
<I>
	amparo
</I>
	appeal against this determination on April&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2014. On February&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2015, this legal proceeding was decided in our favor.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meetings of April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2012, April&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2013, and April&nbsp;23,&nbsp;2014
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Grupo M&eacute;xico and its subsidiary, ITM, have filed lawsuits seeking to void shareholder resolutions adopted at each of our General
	Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meetings from 2012 to 2014. We have responded to each of these lawsuits. Each of these cases has proceeded through all of its phases and awaits judgment; however, as a result of a motion filed by us to join these three
	related actions with the proceedings regarding the Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on September&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2012, the issues in each case will be resolved together with the trial seeking to nullify the resolutions adopted at the
	Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on September&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2012. As a result, these matters are still pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	160
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage167"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
	Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting of September&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2012
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At the Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on September&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2012, duly held by a quorum of 75% of the shares entitled to
	vote, shareholders approved a capital stock reduction, for the fixed portions proportional to the historical value of the capital stock and to the value of the stock as adjusted for inflation through December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, The resolution
	required Ps.870.0&nbsp;million to be paid in cash pro rata among the shares outstanding on a date no later than October&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2012.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2012, we complied with the resolution by making a payment to the Central Securities Depository (S.D. Indeval
	Instituci&oacute;n para el Dep&oacute;sito de Valores, S.A. de C.V.), or &#147;Indeval,&#148; equivalent to Ps.1.639281 per share outstanding. However, after our payment to Indeval, Grupo M&eacute;xico issued a press release announcing that a Mexico
	City civil court had issued a decision that ordered us to immediately and unconditionally suspend the resolution related to the capital reduction. As we were otherwise not properly notified by the court of the injunction, we thereby became aware of
	a lawsuit filed by Grupo M&eacute;xico seeking the suspension of the resolutions adopted at the Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on September&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2012. Despite not being notified by the competent court, and after we had
	complied with the resolutions and completed the required payment, we were then informed by Indeval that, because it had been notified of this judicial injunction that presumably ordered us, not Indeval, to suspend the resolution related to the
	capital reduction, Indeval would suspend the disbursement of the funds deposited by us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of the date of this report, Indeval continues
	to hold the funds allocated for the capital reduction, and we expect that Indeval will continue holding the funds until the injunction is resolved judicially. We have answered the lawsuit and also appealed the decision regarding the suspension of
	the capital reduction approved at the Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting. The case has proceeded through all of its phases and awaits judgment; however, as a result of a motion we filed to join this case with the three pending related actions
	discussed above, the issues in this case will be resolved together with the trial seeking to nullify the resolutions of the General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meetings held on April&nbsp;16, 2012,&nbsp;April&nbsp;16, 2013, and April&nbsp;23, 2014.
	As a result, these matters are still pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Grupo M&eacute;xico, S.A.B. de C.V. and certain of its subsidiaries challenge our participation
	agreement with AMP
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	ITM, a subsidiary of Grupo M&eacute;xico, filed a legal proceeding against us on November&nbsp;4,&nbsp;2011,
	seeking to void AMP&#146;s ownership of our Series&nbsp;BB shares as granted by the participation agreement between AMP and us, which would result in the termination of AMP&#146;s veto, appointment of executives and other special rights.
	Additionally, ITM&#146;s suit sought the repayment of all economic benefits conferred by us upon AMP during the period in which AMP has held our shares. We filed an initial reply in this proceeding on November&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2011. On
	March&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2012, we were notified by our external legal counsel that a ruling was issued in our favor, which found a lack of jurisdiction by the civil court due to the administrative nature of the claim. Although we received notice that this
	proceeding had concluded, a federal court later granted a direct
<I>
	amparo
</I>
	appeal that had been filed by Grupo M&eacute;xico on June&nbsp;6,&nbsp;2012. Therefore, on July&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2012, the legal proceeding was recommenced in the
	appropriate federal civil court. On October&nbsp;22,&nbsp;2013, we filed briefs responding to the plaintiff&#146;s arguments. As of the filing of this report, this proceeding is still pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
</I>
</B>
<B>
	Ejido
</B>
<B>
<I>
	participants at Tijuana, Guadalajara and Puerto Vallarta airports
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	A portion of the lands constituting some of our airports were expropriated by the Mexican government under its power of eminent domain. Prior
	to their expropriation, some of these lands had been
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	161
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage168"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	held by groups of individuals through a system of communal ownership of rural land known as an
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	. Certain of these former
<I>
	ejidos
</I>
	&#146; participants have asserted indemnity
	claims against the Mexican government challenging the expropriation decrees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In the case of our Tijuana airport, our airport
	subsidiary has been joined as an interested third party in the proceedings challenging the 1970 expropriation decree. During 2008, the
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	received an unfavorable ruling, which it appealed, and subsequently, it received a judgment in its
	favor calling for the restitution of 320 hectares of land. Although the precise area affected has yet to be determined, depending on which particular land parcel is to be returned, this could affect the airport&#146;s perimeter and could materially
	disrupt the airport&#146;s current operations.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In addition, certain of the former
<I>
	ejidos&#146;
</I>
	participants are
	currently occupying portions of the property on which we operate Tijuana International Airport. Although the currently occupied portions are not at present essential to the airport&#146;s operations and these former
<I>
	ejidos&#146;
</I>
	participants
	are not currently interfering with the airport&#146;s operations, their presence could limit our ability to expand the airport into the areas they occupy. In addition, there can be no assurance that the former
<I>
	ejidos&#146;
</I>
	participants will
	not seek to disrupt the airport&#146;s operations if their legal claims against the Mexican government are not resolved to their satisfaction.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Similarly, in the case of Guadalajara International Airport, in 2009 two different
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	s commenced proceedings before an agrarian
	court (
<I>
	Tribunal Superior Agrario
</I>
	) against the SCT, seeking to void the expropriation decree of 1975. The case was transferred to the federal justice system, and in a November 2010 ruling in favor of the
<I>
	ejidos
</I>
	, the district court
	ordered the return of all expropriated property to the
<I>
	ejidos
</I>
	and thus voided the specific concession granted to us on expropriated land. Although our Guadalajara airport has been joined only as an interested third party in the proceedings,
	we appealed this decision. On July&nbsp;10,&nbsp;2012, the appellate court reversed and remanded the decision, and on July&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2014, the district court issued a new judgment in favor of one of the
<I>
	ejidos
</I>
	, El Zapote, which both our
	Guadalajara airport and the federal authorities again appealed. As of the date of this report, this appeal is pending. With respect to the second
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	, Santa Cruz del Valle, the district court&#146;s ruling against the Mexican
	government&#146;s 1975 expropriation decree was confirmed by the appellate court and is subject to enforcement against the Mexican government.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	In February&nbsp;10,&nbsp;2014, our Guadalajara airport received a notice from the district court regarding a proceeding by the
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	San Jos&eacute; del Valle claiming approximately five hectares within the airport&#146;s possession. Currently, this case is in the presentation of evidence stage.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In September&nbsp;2013, Puerto Vallarta International Airport received notification of lawsuits related to the
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	Valle de Banderas,
	which claimed the invalidity of the expropriation by the Mexican government of the land on which the airport is located. Participants of the
<I>
	ejido
</I>
	commenced three proceedings against us, our Puerto Vallarta airport and various federal
	authorities for restitution or compensation with respect to 154 hectares of land comprising this airport. The claimants seek, among other things, to invalidate the expropriation decree issued on October&nbsp;9,&nbsp;1957 and, in two of the
	proceedings, are also seeking restitution of the land as they were not part of the expropriation decrees of October&nbsp;9,&nbsp;1957, August&nbsp;20,&nbsp;1990, November&nbsp;24,&nbsp;1993, and April&nbsp;24,&nbsp;1997. These lawsuits are also
	seeking, in part, to void the concession granted to the airport. We have challenged the lawsuits on the basis of a lack of jurisdiction, as the claims were brought in the courts of the State of Nayarit, while our Puerto Vallarta airport is located
	in the State of Jalisco. The superior agrarian court declared the Nayarit court as having jurisdiction, and we have appealed this decision. This proceeding remains pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	The terms of our concession require the Mexican government to provide us restitution for any loss of our use of the land provided for
	in our Mexican concessions. Although no assurance can be given, we believe that the Mexican government would be liable for any operational disruption caused by the proceedings with the
<I>
	ejidos
</I>
	and would have to restore our rights of use for
	the public property assigned to us under the concessions if we were to lose our appeals.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	162
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage169"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Property tax claims by certain municipalities
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We remain subject to ongoing property tax claims that have been asserted against us by the municipal authorities of Mexicali, Tijuana,
	Guadalajara and Hermosillo for the payment of property taxes with respect to the property on which we operate our airports in those cities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The municipality of Hermosillo has initiated efforts to survey the area of our Hermosillo airport in order to determine the amount of property
	taxes owed. We challenged their actions through administrative proceedings filed on July&nbsp;30,&nbsp;2013, October&nbsp;16,&nbsp;2013 and January&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2014. As of the date of this report, we have not received a decision in these
	proceedings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On May&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2010, the municipality of Tlajomulco, the municipality in which our Guadalajara airport is located,
	delivered a notice to the airport in which it seeks payment of property taxes. The notice, however, was factually inaccurate with respect to a number of items, including ownership of the property. As a result, the proceeding was improperly
	commenced, and no further action on our part is needed at this time which is pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In the case of our Tijuana airport, the municipal
	authority issued a second property tax claim against the airport on June&nbsp;8,&nbsp;2005. The court then ordered the temporary encumbrance of certain of our assets, including our concession to operate Tijuana International Airport, pending our
	deposit of a bond with the court as provisional security, in accordance with Mexican judicial procedures, while we await the final resolution of the underlying claims. Although the encumbered assets did not affect the operation of the airport, on
	February&nbsp;9,&nbsp;2006, a bond was issued by a financial institution on behalf of the Tijuana airport for Ps.141.8&nbsp;million (nominal pesos) in order to release the encumbrance. On March&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2008, the Tijuana airport received an
	initial ruling declaring void the tax claim by the municipal authority but upholding the right of the municipal authorities to assess property taxes over commercial areas. Although we appealed the ruling with respect to the assessment of property
	taxes over commercial areas, we also petitioned that the bond be refunded in the interim because the municipality did not appeal any matter in the resolution. Accordingly, on February&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2009, our line of credit for the issuance of the
	bond was cancelled. Our challenge to the second request is still pending. On October&nbsp;20,&nbsp;2010, the municipal authority of Tijuana issued a third request for the repayment of property taxes for 2000 through 2010. We and our legal counsel
	believe that this request for payment of taxes is not valid since local courts had already ruled the tax claims for the years 2005 and 2006 invalid. In conjunction with its third request, the Tijuana municipal authority requested that we make a full
	payment of the claimed taxes of Ps.269.2&nbsp;million within three days of receiving the request. The municipal authority also listed a number of assets that they believed could be seized if payment was not made. Because we and our legal counsel
	believe that this request for repayment is also invalid, we commenced legal proceedings against the municipal authority. The legal proceeding is currently pending. On February&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2013, the Tijuana municipal authority filed a fourth
	property tax claim for the period from 2008 to 2012 against the Tijuana airport in the amount of Ps.15.2&nbsp;million, demanding payment within three business days. On February&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2013, we began an annulment proceeding against the claim.
	On March&nbsp;5,&nbsp;2013 the authority established the amount to be guaranteed, and on March&nbsp;8,&nbsp;2013 we presented a bond to guarantee the amount claimed. As of the date of this report, this proceeding is still pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;24,&nbsp;2014, the Tijuana municipal authority issued a requirement for payment of Ps.233.7&nbsp;million in real estate taxes
	covering the period from 2000 to 2014. On November&nbsp;13,&nbsp;2014, we filed an administrative proceeding for annulment against this requirement, which we consider to be unfounded. On October&nbsp;29,&nbsp;2014, the municipal authority revoked
	the requirement as unfounded, however, on November&nbsp;26,&nbsp;2014, the authority issued a different requirement for payment of PS.234.8&nbsp;million in property taxes for the period from 2000 to 2014, which we again challenged on
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	163
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage170"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	December&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2014. With respect to the municipal authority&#146;s request for us to post a collateral bond guaranteeing the entire amount in question, the court granted judgment in our
	favor and suspended the requirement, which we had challenged on the grounds that we have already guaranteed part of the amount in previous proceedings. This matter has not yet been resolved by the courts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We do not believe that liabilities related to any claims or proceedings against us are likely to have, individually or in the aggregate, a
	material adverse effect on our consolidated financial condition or results of operations should a court determine that these property taxes must be paid in response to any future proceedings.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Federal tax proceedings against La Paz and Morelia airports
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	The Mexican Tax Authority (
<I>
	Servicio de Administraci&oacute;n Tributaria
</I>
	), or &#147;SAT,&#148; in connection with its review for
	the 2005 year, notified us in 2008 and 2009 that under its criteria our La Paz and Morelia airports, among others, incorrectly applied the fiscal amortization rates with regard to the value of their concessions.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On February&nbsp;12,&nbsp;2010, the Morelia International Airport filed an administrative proceeding against the resolution issued by the tax
	authority stating that the airport applied a fiscal amortization rate in excess of its concession value. On October&nbsp;5,&nbsp;2011, our Morelia airport received an unfavorable ruling; therefore, on October&nbsp;26,&nbsp;2011, it filed an appeal
	on constitutional grounds against that unfavorable decision, which was partially ruled in favor of the airport in September&nbsp;2012. Subsequently, the tax authority filed an appeal against this decision, which was resolved against the airport on
	February&nbsp;28,&nbsp;2013. Accordingly, on March&nbsp;14,&nbsp;2013, we paid Ps.2.9&nbsp;million to the tax authority, after which this proceeding was concluded. On November&nbsp;19,&nbsp;2014, the Mexican Tax Authority issued a ruling with the
	calculation of an additional employees&#146; statutory profit sharing, which we appealed. In February&nbsp;2015, the airport received a favorable resolution and the tax authority did not appeal this decision, therefore the legal proceeding was
	concluded in May 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On October&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2011, La Paz International Airport received a favorable decision in the first instance,
	which was appealed by the tax authority. On September&nbsp;7,&nbsp;2012, the court issued a resolution in favor of the tax authority and remanded the case to the lower court with instructions to modify its decision based on the applicable law in
	2005. On November&nbsp;14,&nbsp;2012, the lower court found in favor of the tax authority regarding the income tax, but found the fine to be invalid. The tax authority appealed with regards to the fine. In February&nbsp;2013, our La Paz airport paid
	the corresponding taxes according to the last resolution. In January&nbsp;21,&nbsp;2014, we received confirmation from the court that the fine is invalid. However, on February&nbsp;11,&nbsp;2014, the Mexican Tax Authority filed an appeal. On
	February&nbsp;5, 2016, the court issued a final decision in our favor.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Infractions of the Mexican Securities Law alleged by the CNBV
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2011, we received a formal notice from the CNBV by which it initiated a proceeding against us for alleged violations of
	Mexican disclosure statutes primarily in connection with disputes among AMP&#146;s shareholders during 2010. This notice was the first stage of an administrative proceeding required to impose a fine on us. On June&nbsp;3,&nbsp;2011, we exercised our
	right to appeal the determination of the CNBV and to file evidence to contest this determination.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	On April&nbsp;24,&nbsp;2013, we were
	notified by the CNBV of the imposition of administrative sanctions for the alleged violations. We appealed the sanctions by means of an administrative proceeding before the Fiscal Federal and Administrative Justice Court on June&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We can provide no assurance as to what, if any, additional actions the CNBV may take as part of the administrative proceeding. Nor can we
	provide any assurance that we will be successful in any
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	164
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage171"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	subsequent legal actions we may take in response to the CNBV. If we are not successful in our appeal, the maximum amount of the fine that could be levied against us for all alleged violations is
	approximately Ps.31.0&nbsp;million (approximately U.S.$1.8&nbsp;
	million). As of the date of this report, this appeal remains pending.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_22">
</A>
	DIVIDENDS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The declaration, amount and payment of dividends are determined by a majority vote of our shareholders present at a shareholders&#146; meeting
	and generally, but not necessarily, on the recommendation of the board of directors, which is empowered by Article&nbsp;18 of our bylaws to set our dividend policies. So long as the Series&nbsp;BB shares represent at least 7.65% of our outstanding
	capital stock, the declaration and payment of dividends will require the approval of the holders of a majority of the Series&nbsp;BB shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mexican law requires that at least 5% of a company&#146;s net income each year (after profit sharing and other deductions required by Mexican
	law) be allocated to a legal reserve fund until such fund reaches an amount equal to at least 20% of the company&#146;s capital stock from time to time (without adjustment for inflation). Our legal reserve fund was Ps.840.7&nbsp;million (historical
	value) at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015 (excluding reserve amounts corresponding to 2015 net income).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Mexican companies may pay dividends
	only out of earnings (including retained earnings after all losses have been absorbed or paid up) and only after such allocation to the legal reserve fund. The reserve fund is required to be funded on a stand-alone basis for each company, rather
	than on a consolidated basis. The level of earnings available for the payment of dividends is determined under MFRS. Our subsidiaries, which prepare and report financial information under MFRS, are required to allocate earnings to their respective
	legal reserve funds prior to paying dividends to Grupo Aeroportuario del Pac&iacute;fico, S.A.B. de C.V. We are also required to allocate earnings to our legal reserve fund prior to distributing any dividend payments to our shareholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As a result of the 2014 Fiscal Reform, dividends paid to Mexican individuals or any foreign residents with respect to our Series B shares and
	ADSs are subject to a 10% withholding tax. The definition of dividend for this purpose includes, among others, in addition to declared dividends: (i)&nbsp;interest paid on preferred shares; (ii)&nbsp;loans to shareholders and partners unless the
	loan is established for less than one year, incurred in the operations of the business and meets certain requirements; (iii)&nbsp;payments that are considered non-deductible and benefit the shareholders; (iv)&nbsp;amounts not recognized as a result
	of omissions of income or unrealized purchases; and (v)&nbsp;transfer pricing adjustments to income or expenses as a result of assessments by the tax authorities for related party transactions. The 10% distribution tax would also apply on
	distributions from a branch to the home office. A transitory provision limits the withholding tax on dividends to earnings generated in 2014 and subsequent years. For this purpose, the transitory provision refers to distributions from accumulated
	previously taxed earnings (CUFIN) as of 2013, being free of tax. Taxpayers are currently required to maintain a separate CUFIN account for earnings. Because this withholding tax would be a tax on the shareholders under the Mexican Income Tax Law,
	treaty benefits should be available.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Dividends that are paid from a company&#146;s distributable earnings that have not been subject to
	corporate income tax will be subject to a corporate-level dividend tax (retained against cumulative net income and payable by us) calculated on a gross-up basis by applying a factor of 1.4286 for 2013 and subsequent years. For 2013 and thereafter,
	the corporate tax rate is 30%. This corporate-level dividend income tax on the distribution of earnings may be applied as a credit against Mexican corporate income tax corresponding to the fiscal year in which the dividend was paid or against the
	Mexican corporate income tax of the two fiscal years following the date on which the dividend was paid.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Distributions made by us to our
	shareholders other than as dividends (in the manner described above), including capital reductions, amortization of shares or otherwise, would be subject to taxation in Mexico, including withholding taxes. The tax rates applicable and the method of
	assessing and paying taxes applicable to any such non-dividend distributions will vary depending on the nature of the distributions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	165
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage172"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We paid aggregate dividends of Ps.1.21&nbsp;billion in 2013, Ps.1.59&nbsp;billion in 2014 and
	Ps.1.74&nbsp;billion in 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under our dividend policy adopted at the Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on
	April&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2005, our annual dividend is expected to consist of two components. The first component is a fixed amount, which was Ps.450&nbsp;million for 2005 (for the dividend paid in 2006) and is intended to increase gradually each year.
	Second, the dividend policy contemplates that our annual dividend will include any cash and cash equivalents we hold (as reflected in our balance sheet as of the month-end prior to the dividend payment, after deducting the fixed component) in excess
	of our &#147;minimum cash balance.&#148; For purposes of our policy, the &#147;minimum cash balance&#148; is the amount of cash and cash equivalents that our board of directors determines is necessary to cover the minimum amount of expenses and
	investments expected to be incurred in the fiscal year during which the dividend payment is made and the subsequent fiscal year. Dividends are expected to be made payable in cash and in one or more payments as determined in the relevant ordinary
	shareholders&#146; meeting approving dividends.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	The declaration, amount and payment of dividends pursuant to the policy described
	above are subject to (i)&nbsp;compliance with applicable law regarding the declaration and payment of dividends with respect to any year including the establishment of the statutory legal reserve fund and (ii)&nbsp;the absence of any adverse effect
	on our business plan for the current or subsequent fiscal year as a result of the payment of any dividend. We cannot provide assurance that we will continue to pay dividends or that future dividends will be comparable to our previous dividends. Our
	ability to pay dividends may be further restricted under the unsecured peso-denominated credit agreements into which some of our operating subsidiaries enter from time to time. However, at the date of this report these lines of credit have been paid
	in full. See &#147;Item&nbsp;5,
<I>
	Operating and Financial Review and Prospects &#150; Liquidity and Capital Resources
</I>
	.&#148; Our dividend policy may also be amended at any time by our shareholders.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2015, we had accumulated approximately Ps.2.7&nbsp;billion of distributable earnings that had been subject to the
	corporate income tax and that could be declared at the relevant shareholders&#146; meeting and paid to shareholders free of the corporate level dividend tax, but a 10% withholding tax may apply to Mexican individuals or any foreign residents.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	We pay dividends in pesos. In the case of Series&nbsp;B shares represented by ADSs, the cash dividends are paid to the depositary and, subject
	to the terms of the Deposit Agreement, converted into and paid in U.S. dollars at the prevailing rate of exchange, net of conversion expenses of the depositary and applicable Mexican withholding tax. Fluctuations in exchange rates will affect the
	amount of dividends that ADS holders receive.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_25">
</A>
	TRADING ON THE MEXICAN STOCK
	EXCHANGE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	The Mexican Stock Exchange, located in Mexico City, is the only stock exchange in Mexico. Founded in 1894 and in
	continuous operations since 1907, the Mexican Stock Exchange is organized as a Mexican corporation (
<I>
	sociedad an&oacute;nima burs&aacute;til de capital variable
</I>
	) operating under a concession granted by the Ministry of Finance and Public Credit
	(SHCP). Securities trading on the Mexican Stock Exchange occurs each business day from 8:30&nbsp;a.m. to 3:00&nbsp;p.m., Mexico City time.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Since January&nbsp;1999, all trading on the Mexican Stock Exchange has been effected electronically. The Mexican Stock Exchange may impose a
	number of measures to promote orderly and transparent trading in securities, including the operation of a system of automatic suspension of trading in shares of a particular issuer when price fluctuation exceeds certain limits. The Mexican Stock
	Exchange may also suspend trading in shares of a particular issuer as a result of:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	non-disclosure of material events; or
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	167
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage174"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	changes in the offer or demand, volume traded, or prevailing share price that are inconsistent with the shares&#146; historical performance and cannot be explained through publicly available information.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Mexican Stock Exchange may reinstate trading in suspended shares when it deems that the material events have been
	adequately disclosed to public investors or when it deems that the issuer has adequately explained the reasons for the changes in offer and demand, volume traded, or prevailing share price. Under current regulations, the Mexican Stock Exchange may
	consider the measures adopted by the other stock exchanges in order to suspend and/or resume trading in an issuer&#146;s shares in cases where the relevant securities are simultaneously traded on a stock exchange outside of Mexico.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Settlement on the Mexican Stock Exchange is effected three business days after a share transaction. Deferred settlement is not permitted
	without the approval of the Mexican National Banking and Securities Commission, even where mutually agreed. Most securities traded on the Mexican Stock Exchange are on deposit with Indeval, a privately owned securities depositary that acts as a
	clearinghouse, depositary, and custodian, as well as a settlement, transfer, and registration agent for Mexican Stock Exchange transactions, eliminating the need for physical transfer of securities.
</P>
</EFX_LISTING>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:18PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_ADDITIONAL_INFORMATION>
<A NAME="FIS_ADDITIONAL_INFORMATION"></A>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="8%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
<B>
	Item&nbsp;10.
</B>
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<B>
	Additional Information
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_26">
</A>
</B>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:24PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
<A NAME="D144740D20F_HTM_TOC144740_27">
</A>
	CORPORATE GOVERNANCE
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Organization and Register
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	Grupo
	Aeroportuario del Pac&iacute;fico, S.A.B. de C.V. is a corporation (
<I>
	sociedad an&oacute;nima burs&aacute;til de capital variable
</I>
	) organized under the laws of Mexico under the Mexican General Law of Commercial Corporations (
<I>
	Ley General de
	Sociedades Mercantiles
</I>
	) and the Mexican Securities Market Law. It is registered with the Public Registry of Commerce of Mexico City under the number 238,578.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Purpose
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our main corporate purpose is to
	operate airports pursuant to airport concessions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Bylaws
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	This section summarizes certain provisions of Mexican law and our
<I>
	estatutos sociales
</I>
	(bylaws).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	At our Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting held on October&nbsp;27,&nbsp;2006, our shareholders adopted resolutions amending and
	restating of our bylaws to organize the company as a
<I>
	sociedad an&oacute;nima burs&aacute;til
</I>
	(a form then newly required by law for publicly traded companies in Mexico), and to conform our bylaws to the provisions of the Securities Market
	Law. Many of the changes related to the enhancement of our corporate governance.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<I>
</I>
	During 2010, our Audit Committee proposed,
	to our board of directors, an amendment to our bylaws relating to the Corporate Practices articles (
<I>
	Practicas Societarias
</I>
	, as described in the Mexican Securities Market Law) in order to more closely align our bylaws with the terms of the
	Mexican Securities Market Law with respect to Corporate Practices. After reviewing the amendment proposal, our board of directors instructed the Audit Committee to submit the proposal to the CNBV to obtain their opinion regarding how the amended
	articles compared with the Mexican Securities Market Law, specifically as it relates to Corporate Practices. In response, the CNBV provided their recommendations both with respect to the specific consultation as well as with respect to other
	articles contained in the proposed amendment. We accepted the CNBV&#146;s recommendations and re-submitted the proposed amendments to the CNBV. As of the date of this report, we have not received a response from the CNBV.
<I>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	168
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage175"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Board of Directors
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our bylaws provide that our board of directors will generally have eleven members (increasing to twelve or thirteen members only when necessary
	to preserve minority shareholders&#146; voting rights in cases of multiple appointments by persons with 10% interests (as described below)).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At each shareholders&#146; meeting for the election of directors, the holders of Series&nbsp;BB shares are entitled to elect four directors.
	The remaining members of the board of directors are to be elected by the holders of the Series&nbsp;B shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Each person (or group of
	persons acting together) holding 10% of our capital stock in the form of Series&nbsp;B shares is entitled to appoint one director. The remaining positions on the board of directors will be filled based on the vote of all holders of Series&nbsp;B
	shares that have not elected to appoint a director by virtue of owning 10% of our capital stock. The candidates to be considered for election as directors by the Series&nbsp;B shareholders are proposed to the shareholders by the Nominations and
	Compensation Committee. All directors are elected based on a simple majority of the votes cast at the relevant shareholders&#146; meeting. Our bylaws do not currently require mandatory retirement of directors after they reach a certain age. The
	compensation of our directors is proposed by the Nominations and Compensation Committee to all of our shareholders at shareholders&#146; meetings for their approval. Pursuant to the Securities Market Law, 25% of our directors must be independent
	within the definition of that term specified therein.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Authority of the Board of Directors
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The board of directors is our legal representative. The powers of the board include, among others, the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	to define our strategic planning decisions and approve our annual business plans and investment budgets;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	to approve our Master Development Programs and modifications thereto;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	to call shareholders&#146; meetings and act upon shareholders&#146; resolutions; and
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	to create special committees and grant them the powers and authority as it sees fit, provided that said committees will not be vested with the authorities which by law or under our bylaws are expressly reserved for the
	shareholders or the board of directors.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Meetings of the board of directors will be validly convened and held if a majority
	of the members are present. Resolutions at said meetings will be valid if approved by a majority of the members of the board of directors, unless our bylaws require a higher number. Notwithstanding the board&#146;s authority, under general
	principles of Mexican law, our shareholders, pursuant to a decision validly taken at a shareholders&#146; meeting, may at any time override the board.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Powers of Series&nbsp;BB Directors
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	The Series&nbsp;BB directors are entitled to: (i)&nbsp;appoint and remove our chief executive officer and our other top-level executive
	officers (upon consultation with our Nominations and Compensation Committee); (ii)&nbsp;appoint three members of the Operating Committee and their respective alternates; (iii)&nbsp;appoint 20% of the total members of the Audit Committee, the
	Acquisitions Committee and the Nominations and Compensation Committee (a minimum of one member per committee), and their respective alternatives; and (iv)&nbsp;consent to the appointment of individuals appointed to the Operating Committee who are
	not members of our board of directors or our officers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	169
</P>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	In addition to the foregoing, each of the following actions of our board of directors, among
	certain others, may only occur with the approval of the Series&nbsp;BB directors:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Our bylaws provide that our shares have the following characteristics:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Series&nbsp;B
</I>
	: Series&nbsp;B shares currently represent 85% of our capital, and may represent up to 100% of our share capital. Series&nbsp;B shares may be held by any Mexican or foreign natural person, company or
	entity, except for foreign governments.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<I>
	Series&nbsp;BB
</I>
	: Series&nbsp;BB shares currently represent 15% of our capital and may not represent a greater percentage of our share capital. Like Series&nbsp;B shares, Series&nbsp;BB shares may be held by any
	Mexican or foreign natural person, company or entity, except for foreign governments and subject to the other requirements of our bylaws.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under the Mexican Airport Law and the Mexican Foreign Investments Law (
<I>
	Ley de Inversi&oacute;n Extranjera
</I>
	), foreign persons may not
	directly or indirectly own more than 49% of the capital stock of a
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	170
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage177"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	holder of an airport concession unless an authorization from the Mexican Commission of Foreign Investments is obtained. We have obtained this authorization, and as a consequence these
	restrictions do not apply to our Series&nbsp;B or Series&nbsp;BB shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	All ordinary shares confer equal rights and obligations to
	holders within each series. Series&nbsp;BB shares are subject to transfer restrictions under our bylaws and generally must be converted to Series&nbsp;B shares before they can be transferred. Up to 49% of the Series&nbsp;BB shares can be converted
	into Series&nbsp;B shares at any time. The remaining 51% of Series&nbsp;BB shares could not be converted into Series&nbsp;B shares before August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2009, absent prior approval by the SCT. Thereafter and until August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2014,
	one fifth of such 51% could be converted each year. On or after August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2014, none of the Series&nbsp;BB shares may be converted into Series&nbsp;B shares if (i)&nbsp;the Technical Assistance Agreement between AMP and us has not been
	renewed; and (ii)&nbsp;the Series&nbsp;BB shareholders so request. Notwithstanding the foregoing, if at any time after August&nbsp;25,&nbsp;2014, Series&nbsp;BB shares represent less than 7.65% of our share capital, those shares will be mandatorily
	converted into Series&nbsp;B shares and the Technical Assistance Agreement will be terminated.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Voting Rights and Shareholders&#146; Meetings
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Each Series&nbsp;B share and Series&nbsp;BB share entitles the holder to one vote at any general meeting of our shareholders. Holders of
	Series&nbsp;BB shares are entitled to elect four members of our board of directors and holders of Series&nbsp;B shares are entitled to elect the remaining members of the board of directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Under Mexican law and our bylaws, we may hold three types of shareholders&#146; meetings: ordinary, extraordinary, and special. Ordinary
	shareholders&#146; meetings are those called to discuss any issue not reserved for extraordinary shareholders&#146; meeting. An annual ordinary shareholders&#146; meeting (our &#147;General Ordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting&#148;) must be convened
	and held within the first four months following the end of each fiscal year to discuss, among other things, the report prepared by the board on our financial statements, the appointment of members of the board of directors, the declaration of
	dividends and the determination of compensation for members of the board.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Extraordinary shareholders&#146; meetings (our
	&#147;Extraordinary Shareholders&#146; Meeting&#148;) are those called to consider any of the following matters:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
	the extension of our duration or our voluntary dissolution;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Special shareholders&#146; meetings are those called and held by shareholders of the same series or class to consider any matter particularly
	affecting the relevant series or class of shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	171
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage178"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D144740D20F_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Shareholders&#146; meetings are required to be held in our corporate domicile, which is the city
	of Guadalajara, in the state of Jalisco. Calls for shareholders&#146; meetings must be made by the board of directors or the Audit Committee. Any shareholder or group of shareholders representing at least 10% of our capital stock has the right to
	request that the board of directors or the Audit Committee call a shareholders&#146; meeting to discuss the matters indicated in the relevant request. In certain circumstances specified in Mexican law, any individual shareholder may also make such a
	request. If the board of directors or the Audit Committee fails to call a meeting within fifteen calendar days following receipt of the request, the shareholder or group of shareholders may request that the call be made by a competent court.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Calls for shareholders&#146; meetings must be published in the Mexican Federal Gazette or in one newspaper of general circulation in Mexico at
	least fifteen calendar days prior to the date of the meeting. Each call must set forth the place, date and time of the meeting and the matters to be addressed. Shareholders&#146; meetings will be validly held and convened without the need for a
	prior call or publication whenever all the shares representing our capital are duly represented.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	To be admitted to any shareholders&#146;
	meeting, shareholders must be registered in our share registry and comply with the requirements set forth in our bylaws. Shareholders may be represented at any shareholders&#146; meeting by one or more attorneys-in-fact who may not be our directors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	At or prior to the time of the publication of any call for a shareholders&#146; meeting, we will provide copies of the publication to the
	depositary for distribution to the holders of ADSs. Holders of ADSs are entitled to instruct the depositary as to the exercise of voting rights pertaining to the Series&nbsp;B shares.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	Quorums
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Ordinary
	shareholders&#146; meetings are regarded as legally convened pursuant to a first call when more than 50% of the shares representing our capital are present or duly represented. Resolutions at ordinary shareholders&#146; meetings are valid when
	approved by a majority of the shares present or duly represented at the meeting. Any number of shares represented at an ordinary shareholders&#146; meeting convened pursuant to a second or subsequent call constitutes a quorum. Resolutions at
	ordinary shareholders&#146; meetings convened in this manner are valid when approved by a majority of the shares represented at the meeting.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Extraordinary and special shareholders&#146; meetings are regarded as legally convened pursuant to a first or subsequent call when at least
	75% of the shares representing our capital (or 75% of the relevant series) are present or duly represented. Resolutions at extraordinary shareholders&#146; meetings are valid if taken by the favorable vote of shares representing more than 50% of our
	capital (or 50% of the relevant series).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	Notwithstanding the foregoing, resolutions at extraordinary shareholders&#146; meetings called
	to discuss any of the issues listed below are valid only if approved by a vote of shares representing at least 75% of our capital:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<TR>

	&nbsp;
</TD>

	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>

	any amendment to our bylaws that: (i)&nbsp;changes or deletes the authorities of our committees; or (ii)&nbsp;changes or deletes the rights of minority shareholders;
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	Dividends and Distributions

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; TEXT-INDENT:4%; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
